animal.description:
My name is CHANCE and I'm approximately 2 years and 2 months old male pit bull. I have been at the Agoura Animal Care Center since September 20, 2020. 

Chance came to us from our Lancaster Animal Care Center in September. We noticed immediately he was lame in his hind end. Taken to @malibucoastanimal it was discovered he had a broken femoral head. ? After having a successful surgery, with Dr Dean’s brilliant surgical skills, Chance is recuperating and is ready to find his forever home!  

Chance loves a treat-stuffed Kong, lounging on the sofa in our "real room", belly rubs and stuffies.  He's got lots of energy, seems to be good with large dogs and would be okay with older children (middle school & up).  

If you think that Chance would be a good fit, drop us an e-mail to make an appointment to come meet him!

Send an inquiry to agoura@animalcare.lacounty.gov and please include your contact phone number.

animal.description: Hi there, I'm Fred and I couldn't be more excited to meet you! Meeting new people is one of my favorite things to do. My friends here at the Pet Center like to say that I have a very regal personality, and that I'm very smart and intuitive. I'm also such a good listener and will gladly sit and give you a high five, but only if you have my favorite jerky treats. Some of my other favorite things to do are play with my rope toys, roll in the grass and get belly rubs, and in return I will give you lots of slobbery kisses. I am 65 lbs., 5 years old, and l am looking for my forever home.

Adoption Donation: $350

All dogs are microchipped, neutered, current on all vaccines, heartworm tested and started on Tri Heart Plus; Vectra 3D.

All household members and any dogs from the household need to be present at the time of the adoption.

Our website is always kept 100% up to date with who is currently available.  As soon as animals are adopted, they are moved to the Adopted Pets page so if they are still listed on the Adoptable Dogs or Cats page, they are still available. So keep any eye on the site for any animals being added as available for adoption as new animals are added everyday! We would recommend if you haven’t done so already that you submit a general online adoption application with us so it is on file for when you are ready to come out and adopt. The adoption counselors will be able to show you many that would be a good fit for your family. Animal House Shelter can not guarantee breed or breed mix of our adoptable animals. The animals are posted on the website as a breed or breed mix based on their physical characteristics they most resemble. We also can not guarantee the ages of our adoptable animals or how large puppies will be when fully grown.

Please fill out an online adoption application. Visit our 'Adopt' page to view adoption process steps, policies, requirements and FAQ. View our 'Visit' page for hours and directions to our shelter. We look forward to seeing you soon!

animal.description:
Suki was surrendered to a local vets office. After spending quite some time waiting for the right family, we offered our assistance. 

Suki is healthy American Bulldog mix. She loves people and needs a calm home as an only pet or with someone with experience to work on food aggression. American Bulldogs are known for being loyal, inquisitive dogs with outgoing personalities and affectionate dispositions. Suki is a sweet girl and a survivor. She was deprived of the training she needed as a pup. 

 Suki  is ready for a person or entire family to love. In foster care, she is decompressing and learning she deserves to be comfortable.  She has been around teenage boys and lots of women . 

? 3 years

? House trained

? Spayed 

? UTD on vaccines 

? Heartworm negative 

?? Microchipped

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Maribel (Mar-ee-bell), but I usually go by Mari (Mar-ee).  I an approximately 10 years young and  in good health.  My mom died unexpectedly, and though her family tried to find me a new home, I ultimately ended up at Legacy Boxer Rescue.  I have a 7 yr. old foster brother who is around 75 lbs. He's my friend, but it took about a month to warm up to playing with him because he is so big and barks loudly as he plays.  I don't bark often, but I certainly know how to speak my mind! And I do love eating!

I have a saucy personality and a face that sometimes looks like I'm mad or serious. Really I'm quite a happy girl. I love long walks, and still have energy to chase a ball or toy when I get back home.  And in true boxer fashion, I love to play keep away with the item once I have it.

Although I do not jump up on people, I am quite intense about chasing the ball/toy and could accidentally knock over a toddler. My foster family doesn't know how I would act around young children as they don't have any, but based on my friendliness to people in general, they think I'd do fine with supervised pet educated children. I am house trained and will tolerate a crate.  I have very good manners on a leash and love to prance up to new people since I'm friendly.  My intake notes say I'm good with cats, but I think what they meant is that I am highly interested in fast furry things and very good at chasing them!  I haven't caught one yet, but my foster mom thinks I might not be very gentle if I caught one. I do know sit, stay, down, wait commands.  I also know come, but sometimes i like to act like I didn't hear you.  But I can sure hear a snack bag opening from the back yard!

My favorite thing is having lots of time with my family.  I like to be as close to them as possible.  And what girl doesn't like a cozy blanket to snore in!  If you think you might like a sassy sweet older gal to spend time with, please let me know so we can meet!


If you are interested in adopting me, please fill out our adoption application to begin the process at http://savetheboxers.com/adoptionapp.php.

If you aren't able to adopt at this time, please consider making a much needed, tax-deductible donation to Legacy Boxer Rescue at http://savetheboxers.com/donate.php.

animal.description:
GEO PET: My adoption fee has been sponsored.

Kane is so dear to so many at the shelter. Could you imagine being tethered your whole life and then FINALLY, coming inside to a world of strange sights, sounds, and people!

At 8 years old, Kane does have some eye issues where he is on daily meds. This may be one of the reasons he does not like strangers and men.

He also does not do well around other animals, which makes sense. If you were outside and limited on how far you could move or run, you would be on the defense of anything entering your space too.

He met the WSBT-TV cameraman, Mark for the pet segment airing Sunday. At first he barked at him, but as we did the segment, he started walking towards the camera and rubbing past Mark. He is definitely a boy who needs a slow, calm approach.

Kane is spoiled by staff at the shelter. He gets his breakfast burrito here and there, cuddles out of his kennel, and leisure walks around the shelter.

This big boy has been at the shelter since April, and became adoptable in October. He is currently the longest term adoptable dog at the shelter. His friend Cinnamon found a place to call home for the holidays. Now it is his turn!

Kane appears to be potty trained, BUT we always encourage new owners to pretend the new pup is not until everyone is used to the new routine.

animal.description:
Meet Hummer
Hummer is an amazing dog. He was surrendered on October 10, 2020 when his owners couldn’t be found and his heroes who fostered him were unable to keep him. 
Hummer is a gorgeous six year old German Shepherd/ Retriever mix. He has a beautiful chocolate and white coat. He weighs 60 pounds. Hummer is house-broken, loves car rides and going for hikes and long walks with his person. Hummer likes being with other dogs and might benefit by having a doggie companion to keep him company. Hummer will do best in a quiet, calm house with older children. He chases cats and will need to be in a home without them.
Gaining trust will be important for his new person. Hummer is showing signs of past abuse. He appears afraid of sudden movements to grab hold of him and he’s very head shy. He may have been hit about the head and leashes jerked on and off of him. He’ll duck to protect himself. It’s heartbreaking to see these behaviors. But with a kind and gentle family who understands his fears, we think they’ll be able to help him forget his past and help him grow in confidence and trust. The shelter environment is also hard on Hummer. Every day he becomes a bit more anxious. He doesn’t know what’s happening to him or how he found himself ‘locked-up.’ We’ve moved his kennel so he can see the outside and we try and give him outside time as much as possible to ease his anxiety. These are new behaviors for him. Per his foster family, he’s a much different dog when he’s away from the shelter and with people he knows and trusts. He’s much more relaxed, affectionate and happy-go-lucky. We hope his forever family comes for him soon so he can leave the shelter behind and begin to live and love again. 
If you’re looking for your best buddy and are able to open your heart and home to a dog needing some TLC, Hummer might be the one for you. He is a special boy with an incredible personality, he just needs that special person to give him a chance at a happy life. 
Call 706-865-4135 for information on additional health services provided as part of the adoption fee.  If interested in one of our puppies or dogs, please submit an application online or at the shelter. Applications can be submitted online at: https://www.charlessmithgallhumanesociety.org/page/dog-adoption-application 
Once an application is submitted online, you will receive an email saying your application has been successfully submitted.  If you don’t receive this email within 24 hours, please check to make sure all application fields were completed or please call our shelter at 706-865-4135. All adopters must complete an approval process which involves a reference check with current/recent vet and a brief home visit if located in the immediate area. We do permit out of state adoptions. Adopters MUST come to the shelter to transport their new family member home. We do not ship nor do we transport them to their new homes. Adoption policies and application procedures are detailed at the shelter website: http://smithgallhumanesociety.org/ under tab All Adoptable Animals.
Charles Smithgall Humane Society (CSHS) is a No kill shelter. Animals in our care remain safe with us until adopted. Resident animals are primarily owner relinquished and also accepted from local Animal Control. The facility usually is operating at capacity with a list of animals waiting for space to open.
Adoptions and meet and greets are being scheduled by appointment only. Please call our office, email us or complete an application and someone will be in touch just as soon as they can. 
Location: 4823 Helen Hwy., Sautee, GA 30571, Phone: 706-865-4135
Email: smithgallhumanesociety@windstream.net
Our shelter in Sautee GA is located about 3 miles south of the alpine town of Helen in northeast GA.

animal.description:
Ellie
Labrador Retriever Mix
Gender: Female
DOB: 08/01/2018
Adoption Fee: $175
PLEASE READ BIOGRAPHY BEFORE APPLYING FOR ADOPTION.
Hi there! I'm Ellie! I'm a sweet, playful, energetic, and funny girl! I love to go for a run, swim, or a long hike. I love toys, balls, and treats! I am a very special girl. I will REQUIRE a home with patience and someone willing to continue my training. 
Ellie has been trained on an e-collar and knows some commands. She was trained and housed for 3 weeks with a specialty trainer that heard of her story. Ellie was adopted from a shelter last year and the owners were advised by a ""trainer"" (not affiliated) to keep her crated for 20 hours a day, and put her on a medication called Trazadone for anxiety. She was on a very high dose of that medication. She has since been tapered down to a low dose, and there is a possibility that she can be tapered down and taken off the medication under the supervision of a veterinarian. Ellie has to be on a strict schedule and exercise regimen to release her energy. Ellie gets along with other dogs. That being said, some dogs do not like her excitement and won't tolerate her. She will need to be slowly introduced to other dogs if so desired. She has been to dog parks with a volunteer and has played well with a few select dogs that tolerated her excitement. She would do well to have a regular playmate as that will stimulate her brain in a good way and expel her energy as well. If you are interested in adopting or fostering Ellie, please submit an adoption application at www.humanemorgan.org/adopt/Please read the animal bios completely before requesting additional information as we do our best to answer the most frequently ask questions in these bios. 

In order to adopt one of our animals an application must be submitted and approved. You can find these applications by going to http://humanemorgan.org/index.php?page=adoption 

ABOUT ADOPTING FROM THE HSMC: 
The shelter address is 1170 Fairground Rd. Madison, GA 30650. For more information on any of our pets, please feel free to email us at INFO@HUMANEMORGAN.ORG give us a call at 706-343-9977. 
All dogs are heartworm negative, current on vaccines/dewormings, and microchipped. 
All cats are FeLv/FIV negative, current on vaccines/dewormings, and microchipped. 
We are open 10am-5pm Monday-Saturday, we schedule our last adoption at 4pm everyday to allow our staff enough time to feed and walk dogs. 
We are an animal shelter and therefore are not able to individually potty train our residents. Many adult dogs do arrive ""house broken"" however due to animal behavior any change in environment will make an emotional impact on the animals and therefore initiate unwanted behaviors during the acclamation period. Please keep this in mind. Puppies do not have the biological maturity to maintain absolute bladder or bowel control and will require a certain degree of potty training and house breaking. Please consider the time and commitment it takes to provide the necessary building blocks for these special babies, prior to submitting your application. 
If you have any questions please email us at info@humanemorgan.org and provide name of the animal you are interested in, in the subject line. 
Thank you, HSMC Staff 

ADOPTION FEES Adoption Fees may change without notice. Always verify the fee when finalizing the adoption. 
~ Cats and Kittens ~ 
* Under 1 Year = $100 
* 1-5 Years = $75 
* Over 5 Years = $50 
** Purebred cats and kittens may be subject to special pricing 

~ Mix Breed Dogs ~ 
* Under 1 Year = $200 
* 1 -3 Years = $175 
* 4-8 Years = $150 
* Over 8 Years = $100

~ Purebred and Designer Breed Dogs ~ 
* Under 1 Year = $375 
* 1-3 Years = $350 
* 4-8 Years = $275 
* Over 8 Years = $150 

~ Medical and Special Needs ~ 
We have rescued dogs and cats which require additional medical care or that have special needs which are not life threatening. In these cases we may require a higher fee to help recoup the costs of their care while at our rescue.

animal.description: Isn't Flax handsome? This dog is truly a transformation. He came to Labs and More severely underweight, missing fur and in desperate need of medical care. He has spent the last few weeks in a foster home and look at him now! He's healthy, happy and ready for a forever home! Flax is about 5 years old and we think he's a Shepherd mix with possibly Akita. True to his breed mix, he is very smart, playful and has a lot of energy. He will need an active family that can work out his mind and body every day. He has learned his basic commands but still needs to refine his manners and still likes to pull on leash. He's just so excited for his next adventure! Sometimes he doesn't realize his own size and gets a little rambunctious at playtime so he may be a little much for small children. He is friendly with new people and gets along with other dogs but thinks all kitties should be chased so needs a home with no cats. Flax is affectionate and loves to be pet, and he would prefer a home where his humans are home more often than not. He would be a great adventure buddy as he loves car rides, exploring trails and playing in the water. If you are interested in meeting Flax, please submit an adoption application on our website. If you're already approved to adopt or if you've adopted from Labs and More before, connect with your adoption coach for the next steps. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. Thank you for rescuing.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! animal.description: Find your new exercise bestie in Pita! She is around 3 years old and we think she is a Belgian Malinois and Shepherd mix. This girl is always ready to hop in the car for her next adventure at your side! True to her breed mix, she is a very high energy dog and will need an active family ready to commit to training and working out Pita's mind and body every day. She needs a lot more than a couple walks around the neighborhood every day. She runs alongside her foster mom while she bikes for exercise and would love a family that enjoys daily hiking or looking for a daily running partner. Once she gets her exercise out, she is sweet and easygoing. Pita is very smart and has learned to heel on leash and several basic commands, including Sit, Down, Leave It, Wait, and Go to Your Bed. She tolerates the cats in her foster home but would love to chase them if given the chance. If she went to a home with kitties, they will already need to be dog savvy and she will need a strong pack leader that will make her mind her manners. She is still working on how to settle down and properly interact with other dogs. For now, she would do best as an only dog in her home and isn't a dog for dog parks, dog beaches or dog daycare. Pita would also do best with a family that is home more often than not. She is still learning it's ok to be alone when her foster family leaves and what she should and should not chew on. Pita will need a confident, dedicated family ready to set firm boundaries and continue her training. In return, you will get a loving and loyal companion for life. animal.description:
This little lady came into the rescue through Louisiana. Her shelter and rescue advocate kept her safe through the hurricane and she is now with her foster in TX. She is approximately 3 years of age and is such a goof! She is HW+ but has almost completed treatment. She appears to be kennel trained and housebroken. 

Her foster home is learning about her by the day. Shes learning the resident dogs in the home and likes before school belly rubs from the kiddos in the home! So far, she has been friendly and non-reactive with the people and dogs with whom she has come into contact. She knows some basic commands and is a bundle of energy! Nola is playful and shows lots of ball/toy drive.This girl can't wait to find her forever home!

If you have questions about Nola please reach out by email to info@MADrescueinc.org or kaeli@madrescueinc.org to speak directly to her adoption coordinator. 

If you are interested in adopting Nola, please complete an application at this link https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/24689/generic . 

We are an official 501C3 organziation that does not have a physical location. Our home address is in Michigan, however, the majority of our dogs are not located in Michigan. The physical location of each our our dogs is posted with the name of the pet or in the title area. If you are within 4 hours of the pet, please be prepared to pick the pet up. We do provide transport assistance, however, the applicant must drive 50% of the total distance of the transport. 

The information that we have available is in our posting. If you would like to discuss this animal additionally please fill out this application. Applications that are completed in our process and being considered as a match will speak to the foster home to gain more information about our adoptable dog. 

You may also call our toll free number at 844-MAD-RESQ or 844-623-7377. 

Additional information about all of our dogs for adoption can be located at our website MAD Rescue Inc

If you have ANY QUESTIONS or are truly interetsed in adopting any animal from PAW Animal Shelter Please, fillout an adoption application FIRST! WE are a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4 and do not always have time to answer every question asked by so many. If you are a good fit for the animal you are interested in -we will call to speak with you, If we feel you are not a good fit , we will contact you about other pets that may be a good fit for your home. Many people are losing the opportunity to adopt the animal they want because they fail to put in an application and the pet was adopted before we could answer your email. .If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility..

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

animal.description:
Bonded pair must go together!

Pugsy (bonded with Lilly)
-approx. age 7
-potty trained and pee pad trained and uses the doggie door to access the fenced patio

-Likes: Pugsy likes toys and balls but mostly likes to play with Lilly while Lilly plays with the toys. She loves to lay in the sun, even when it's hot. Very affectionate.
-Dislikes: Barks at the delivery man, recycle truck, sounds in general, and is more jumpy than Lilly. She's the timid one and will generally stay behind me if I'm walking around the house, but does welcome cuddles and pets, lap time, etc.

-okay in crate: Yes, will get in crate on demand and sometimes go in on her free will, especially if Lilly is already in the crate. Does not sleep in the crate overnight, so not sure if she would whine.
-okay on leash: Like Lilly, Pugsy loves to walk on the leash but is so excited that she pulls.
-okay when meeting other dogs: No, we keep our distance, as they are not socialized to other dogs.

Pugsy is not as bright as Lilly, but I was able to train her to get into the crate and use the doggie door, both took a while. We haven't gotten much farther than that.

They were both easily transitioned to healthier food and treats. Earlier on, Lilly would eat all of Pugsy's food, if she was allowed too. She doesn't do that now, but I do generally watch them both eat before I take them out.

Come see this pup on Saturdays during adoption event hours. Please email Linda at lbredfire@sbcglobal.net or call WT&F's Dog Team voicemail 707-812-9030 to get a jump on the process, ask questions, and/or to confirm they will be there. Dog adoptions are held outside Napa Petco every Saturday - 12:30pm to 4:00pm.
This dog comes spayed/neutered, microchipped, vaccinated, dewormed, heartworm tested negative, and more with an adoption fee/donation to Whiskers, Tails and Ferals in Napa, CA. See more information at http://whiskerstailsandferals.org/.

-potty trained and pee pad trained, but does drink a lot of water so needs to go out more regularly. Uses the doggie door to access the fenced patio. She also does have excited leaky pee accidents, so I give her loves after she has gone out in the morning or I have just returned home, etc.

-Likes: Loves squeaky tennis balls and squeaky plush toys. Likes to play fetch but mostly teases with the return, rather than dropping the ball/stick for you to throw again. I'm working with her to learn 'drop it'. Very affectionate and loves to be on your lap.
-Dislikes: Barks at the delivery man, recycle truck, etc, but not as much as Pugsy. Is able to get to know usual visitors over time, and will greet them lovingly. My sister visited once a week for 3 weeks and they are now friends. Dislikes the mobile groomer but is easily groomed, including nails trimmed and dryer.

-okay in crate: Yes, goes to the crate on her own, and naps there, etc. I do not crate them overnight, so not sure if they would whine if in the crate for that long.
-okay on leash: Loves walks but pulls on leash and is overly excited.
-okay when meeting other dogs: Not socialized to other dogs, very strongly bonded to Pugsy.

Lilly is very smart and treat motivated. She will get in the crate on demand, sit, go to bed, go potty, go poop (I trained with bits of hotdog) and I'm sure eager to learn many other things.

Come see this pup on Saturdays during adoption event hours. Please email Linda at lbredfire@sbcglobal.net or call WT&F's Dog Team voicemail 707-812-9030 to get a jump on the process, ask questions, and/or to confirm they will be there. Dog adoptions are held outside Napa Petco every Saturday - 12:30pm to 4:00pm.
This dog comes spayed/neutered, microchipped, vaccinated, dewormed, heartworm tested negative, and more with an adoption fee/donation to Whiskers, Tails and Ferals in Napa, CA. See more information at http://whiskerstailsandferals.org/.
Visit our Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/whiskerstailsandferals/

animal.description:
7 month old Puppy Bear is a very smart and active puppy. He will thrive in a home that understands that and gives him a job to do. He is mostly potty trained, crate trained and is busy practicing his good puppy skills. He knows sit, down, wait, and is learning to walk nicely on a leash. His favorite game is ball, and he will play for hours!!

Looking for a hiking buddy? He is ready to sign up. Do you need a sous chef? He loves assisting in the kitchen. He is living with another resident dog and cat. He is tolerant of his kitty roommate, but sometimes needs a reminder that his is much bigger, and needs to play nice.

Small children may not work for Puppy Bear due to his exuberance. Older middle school or high school children are fine.

Please remember, adopting a puppy is not everyone's cup of tea. As cute as they are - puppies demand a large investment of time, patience, and training. They are inquisitive, have endless energy and get into just about everything. They dig, chew, and seemingly never stop! Think long and hard about your lifestyle.

If you are not willing to invest the time and training to ensure your puppy matures into the wonderful dog - then please consider an older dog.

Please go to our website and complete an adoption application at:

/https://www.gsroc.org/application/

An adoption counselor will contact you to go over your application and assist you in determining which dog may be best for your particular situation.

animal.description:
Alexander is 1 year old and 50 lbs. He is deaf, but that doesn't stop him from running around the yard and playing with the other dogs. He is a curious, and energetic boy who chases his shadow and tail when not chasing the other dogs. You have to get his attention with hand movements....don't surprise him, it scares him.
Came from home with youngsters - he adores his people and, as you can see, his bubble baths.
He is back with us to learn to not jump up on people. Not pleasant, especially for petite or senior folks. So Alex is taking some training. However, he is a sweet boy that would love a home.
Though he cannot hear, communication with the animals is telepathic. He knows what you're saying.
Please find our applications and valuable information under 'Adopt a dog'* on our website: *www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.
*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *

Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

Please note: If you are viewing this profile anywhere other than Beagles & Buddies own website, you are not receiving full info. Visit info on pet here.

animal.description:
Gemini is a 1 year old Boxer & American Bully mix per a Embark DNA test. She came to us in June 2020. Her owner had recently acquired her from a relative. She had fallen off the bed and broken her back leg. We had her leg plated. Then she got happy tail. This is where they are super happy and wag a lot. The end of the tail hits stuff and blood goes everywhere. She had her tail amputated as a result. Gemini recently completed a 2 week board and train. learn more obedience. The trainers are completely positive. She knows the following commands: paw, sit, down, stay, front position, heel, leave it, back, and watch me. 

Gemini is a large active dog and would do best in a home without small children due to her size. She is not aggressive but often when excited she forgets her size. She is very intelligent and a quick learner. Gemini needs an active home that will also keep her mentally stimulated. Gemini is good with other dogs and likes to play a lot. She does play rough with other dogs. She shouldn’t be in a home with small furry dogs or cats due to prey drive.

She's had multiple great exams. She had an xray to clear her leg. She's had multiple fecals and urinalysis. She is up to date on vaccinations,flea, and heartworm prevention. She is heartworm negative, spayed, and microchipped. She's on science diet prescription cd for high ph levels in her urine. She's on joint supplements. She's on nexgard as she showed signs of potential demodex mange. This is not contagious. The nexguard flea prevention does not allow any mange growth.
She's located in New Orleans LA but she can be adopted anywhere. We'd be willing to help with transport costs.

Here are two videos playing with a large unneutered dog:
https://youtu.be/zyT9Z5cnR34
https://youtu.be/jIt-kiIqcFM

Here is a few commands:

animal.description:
Nessie was originally purchased by an older person who was not able to care for her and surrendered her to a shelter.  She was then rehomed to a home with a male dog, who she did not get along with.  She is selective with other dogs, and would do best as a solo dog.  She is a dominant female, which is common in this breed.  She is very intelligent and loving, just does not want to share her people with other dogs. Nessie does not do well with cats. According to her last owner Nessie does know how to sit, give you a paw, sometimes lay down, and sit, and give you both paws. She is fine with children, however we do recommend a home for her with older teenage children.  

We suggest obedience training for all newly adopted pyrs, to help you create a special bond with you and your new friend, and so you have a well behaved canine. Great Pyrenees are willing to learn, but are not as eager to comply with commands as much as other breeds. They are bred to be independent thinkers. Applicants must be over 25, own their own home and all children in household must be over 15 years old. Your resident pets must be up to date on vaccines, sterilized, you must have a good history of vet care for them, and you must have used heartworm preventative year round for your dogs. 


Nessie will be placed as an inside pet with outside privileges. You MUST have a securely fenced yard accessible from your home. Invisible fencing does not work with this breed and they will take the shock for the freedom.  Great Pyrenees are bred to roam and will create their own territory if not secured, which can led to them being lost, hit by vehicles or shot by people who see them as a threat. The breed is not a good off leash dog, and cannot be trusted to not run away.  A Great Pyrenees off leash is a " DisAPyr." 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please complete the appropriate application on our website, www.igpr.org under the Adopt tab. 

All of our dogs marked as needing foster homes are also available for adoption.  If a dog is listed on this site, it is available.  No need to contact us to see if it is,  We do require you  complete the adoption application prior to meeting a dog.

We also offer a foster to adopt program. You foster the dog, and have first right of refusal on them if an approved application is submitted for them. 

In fostering a dog, the dog comes to you fully vetted. and groomed. You provide good quality food, grooming, and we provide the heartworm preventative and medical care, if needed* .(*Based on approval from IGPR.)

Adoption fee is $350

We recommend obedience training for all newly adopted pyrs, to help you create a special bond with you and your new friend, and so you have a well behaved canine. Great Pyrenees are willing to learn, but are not as eager to comply with commands as much as other breeds. They are bred to be independent thinkers. Applicants must be over 25, own their own home and all children in household must be over 6 years old. Your resident pets must be up to date on vaccines, sterilized, you must have a good history of vet care for them, and you must have used heartworm preventative year round for your dogs. 


Max will be placed as an inside pet with outside privileges. You MUST have a securely fenced yard accessible from your home. Invisible fencing does not work with this breed and they will take the shock for the freedom.  Great Pyrenees are bred to roam and will create their own territory if not secured, which can led to them being lost, hit by vehicles or shot by people who see them as a threat. The breed is not a good off leash dog, and cannot be trusted to not run away.  A Great Pyrenees off leash is a " DisAPyr." 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please complete the appropriate application on our website, www.igpr.org under the Adopt tab. 

All of our dogs marked as needing foster homes are also available for adoption.  If a dog is listed on this site, it is available.  No need to contact us to see if it is,  We do require you  complete the adoption application prior to meeting a dog.

We also offer a foster to adopt program. You foster the dog, and have first right of refusal on them if an approved application is submitted for them. 

In fostering a dog, the dog comes to you fully vetted. and groomed. You provide good quality food, grooming, and we provide the heartworm preventative and medical care, if needed* .(*Based on approval from IGPR.)

Adoption fee is $250

Meet our tiny Mona! She is a very dainty Chihuahua girl weighing in at about 4lbs. Mona has most likely not had the best life and is very uncertain of humans. It took a couple of weeks to warm up to foster mom, but now she is very bonded to foster mom. Mona is not crazy about the other dogs in the house and is quite bossy about the dinner bowl and sharing mom's lap. She's enjoying having a warm bed and a better diet now, but only has 3 teeth so she prefers canned food and small kiblet dry food. We believe she is at least 6 years old. Mona's family decided they did want to care for her any longer, were moving and did not wish to take her. Mona would like to find a special human that is going to love her and give her a secure home and have lots of patience with her (this is very important). Mona's ideal home should be:
-no young children
-no other dogs or maybe one other dog that can put her in her place without harming her
-no cats
-no men unless they are patient and willing to give her time (She will warm up eventually. She now likes foster mom's boyfriend mostly.)

animal.description:
~Tucker came to Almost Home Dog Rescue from Alabama. He was meant to be a hunting dog but that wasn't the right fit for him. He did see neglect & was very skinny. He is now gaining weight & will probably be about 50lbs. and is 2 years old.

He is good with other dogs & people. He can become startled if someone reaches for him when he is sleepy so he would do best in a family without young children. He prefers more quiet home atmosphere. Most of the time he goes with the flow once his routine is established with his people. He is housebroken. He loves to walk on the leash. He does enjoy a fence in yard to wander on his own & run if possible. He loves to settle in with his people at the end of the day & sleeps through the night on a doggie bed or on the couch. He is looking for a best friend so a single person household or a couple looking for a companion dog would suit him as well.

Tucker is housebroken, crate trained (if necessary, but doesn't love it) and rides well in the car. He hasn't been around cats so that's an unknown.

Please email us at AlmostHome4Dogs@yahoo.com to find out if Tucker is the right one for you! (Local adoptions preferred - Philadelphia and tri-state area [South Jersey and northern Delaware] only.)

PLEASE READ BEFORE CONTACTING US!
We are NOT a shelter: All of our dogs live in private homes with foster families. Come and meet the Almost Home dogs and their fosters at our Meet & Greet events, where you can learn more about our wonderful dogs from the people who live with them, find out which dogs are on their way and when they'll arrive, and fill out an application to adopt or foster.

We cannot adopt to homes where electric-shock fencing systems or training collars are used. For more information on the dangers of electric-shock collars, please visit banshockcollars.ca/studies.php and http://www.hollysden.com/say_no_to_shock.htm (scroll down and click on the "Invisible Fencing Systems" link).

We do not have an online adoption application; to request an application, e-mail us at AlmostHome4Dogs@yahoo.com. To speed e-mail processing time, be sure to note the name of the dog you are inquiring about in the Subject line. For Meet & Greet times and locations, visit our home page, where you also will find information on our adoption process and fees.

FOSTER FAMILIES ARE LIFESAVERS!! Can you open your heart and home for a few weeks to homeless shelter dog? Remember, by fostering a dog, you save TWO lives - that of your foster dog, and that of the dog who takes his place in the shelter! Come to a Meet & Greet and find out if fostering is for you - there's no reward quite like the feeling that you've saved a life ... or two!

animal.description:
KELTON, MALE, 18 MONTHS OLD, LAB/WEIMARANER MIX, 40 POUNDS

KELTON IS BEING FOSTERED IN THE RICHMOND VA AREA. IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN KELTON, PLEASE GO TO WWW.MOMSVA.ORG AND COMPLETE AN APPLICATION. 

Kelton is a 1 ½ year old lab mix.  He weighs about 40 lbs and is medium size.  Kelton is all about playing with his friends, chewing on bones, destroying toys to get the squeaker.  He loves to go for walks and car rides.  In the yard Kelton loves running around with his friend, Daisy to see who is the fastest. He loves stalking her and surprising her with a big pounce.   He loves cuddling with his foster mom either in bed or on the sofa.  He is crate trained and house trained.  Kelton loves to talk to you when he wants something or it is bed time.  Even in his crate, he will talk to you with little woofs to let you know that he has to go to the bathroom.  His little woofs are just the cutest. 

 

Kelton is working on keeping down from the counters.  But he is a fast learner and we know that he will get it soon.  He does love to learn new tricks and loves to be rewarded for doing them right.  He loves ice, carrots, and any dog treats.  His favorite is frozen peanut butter in his Kong with a frozen carrot in it to lick and chew on when he has to go into his crate.

 

Kelton would do best in a house with a fenced in yard.  He would also do best with another dog to play with since that is his favorite thing to do.  Kelton is an awesome dog and has this look and head tilt that tells you he is listening to you.

 

If you can’t resist a handsome face, go to www.momsva.org and complete an application to see if you could be a match.

animal.description:
Loki is a 2-3 year old Pit Bull mix who was rescued from Animal Control literally minutes before he was scheduled to be euthanized. He’s fixed and up to date on vaccinations. Look at his beautiful blue and white coat and awesome markings! What a pretty boy!

Loki spent time in a boarding facility until a foster home could be found. He is a complicated and sweet guy who is too smart for his own good. He CANNOT be with other male dogs or kittens. He lives with two female Pit mixes and is good with them. I wouldn’t recommend children because of his temperament, nor a first time dog owner. He needs a calm and stable home with experienced dog person/people who understand the breed. 

The vet called Loki “on guard”. He’s anxious and I would wager there’s some sort of abuse history. You have to be very careful to not startle him or try to touch him without him seeing your hands first. He takes 40mg of generic Prozac daily to help him stay calmer and more comfortable. It is inexpensive through Walmart or other pharmacies.  

Loki loves car rides and can walk on a leash. He doesn’t like to be shut in his crate but will nap in there when we leave the door open. He is house trained and very good about letting you know when he needs to go outside. 

Loki loves to run and go for walk. He needs a secure, fenced in yard because he likes to roam.  He is terrified of thunderstorms and usually waits them out in our windowless laundry room. 

Adoption Fee $150

Foster is Shelly/Kelly

Likes: Playing with the other dogs in the home, snuggling with humans and her dog friends
Dislikes: Loud noises
Personality: Starlight is shy and timid at first but once she is comfortable, she loves hitting the backyard for some zoomies. She is your typical puppy so she will help herself to anything she thinks she can chew and LOVES toys.
Temperament: Timid, we are just now starting to earn her trust after about a month.
Energy Level: Spurts of high energy/zoomies throughout the day. Also ok with hanging out and observing the activities of the home
Good with: Dogs and Kids over 6 years old
Not good with: NOT cat tested, timid around men but warms up eventually
House Trained: 90% house trained, will have an occasional accident every now and again
Crate Trained: Yes, this is her safe place, will require a crate in her new home
Challenges: Due to her lack of trust in people we are slowly working on basic commands but must work at her pace
Medical: Still slightly underweight.
Perfect Home: Star's perfect home would have another dog that could match her energy and want to play regularly. She loves running and is fast so a fenced in yard is required for her safety. She is also nimble so a 6ft fence would be preferred. She is easily spooked and will retreat to her crate or another safe space until she feels comfortable. Starlight currently loves her 12 and 15 year old foster kids, but she must initiate the want for affection on her terms.
Fostered in Camp Hill, PA.
Application Fees, Adoption Donations and Rescue Policy: Please know that 100% of our funds are used for rescuing the dogs.
Our rescue policy requires the following:

Adopters must have their primary residence in one of the following states: Pennsylvania, Ohio, New Jersey, Delaware, Maryland, West Virginia, Virginia, and parts of North Carolina and and parts of New York.
We will not adopt a giant breed dog to homes where the dog will have access to highly varnished hardwood steps inside the home. Any inside steps to which the dog(s) have access, must have carpeting, securely fixed stair treads, or a non-skid surface. We encourage you to remediate potential safety issues while your application is under review, prior to the home visit.
Methods or devices using pain or force on the dog to control the dog, or to deter undesirable behavior is prohibited.
Applications for giant breed dogs must be submitted by the property owner.
Homes with children under 6 years of age will not be approved for adoption.
Homes with children should have a fenced yard.
Pets currently in the applicant's home must have a history of appropriate veterinary care. Veterinary records will be checked.
All references must be checked before any visitation of the dog is permitted at the foster home.
All family members must be present during the home visit to the applicant's home.
Any dog(s) in the applicant's home must have an introductory meeting with the rescue dog being considered, before any adoption can be completed.
Homes with intact dogs will not be approved for adoption. Exceptions to this policy can be found on the Adoptable Dog Page.

For additional information please review our FAQs or contact: mastiffstomutts@gmail.com
Mastiffs To Mutts Rescue reserves the right to approve or deny any adoption that occurs through this organization without disclosure. We reserve the right to make exceptions for special circumstances. 2/1/21 1:57 PM

IMPORTANT!!!   All adoptions are by appointment only going forward and are spaced 30 minutes apart. PLEASE call the shelter directly during business hours for more information (see number below).  You need to make sure that the animal in which you have an interest is still available and to set up an appointment to meet the specific animal.  Once you arrive at the shelter for your scheduled appointment, please follow the directions that you were given over the telephone. If you are running late for your appointment or will be unable to make your scheduled appointment time, notify staff immediately. This will enable them to schedule that time for another prospective adoptive family. If necessary, they will be able to reschedule your appointment to a more convenient time.  

REGGIE arrived in October in poor condition with broken canine teeth and his ribs showing.  Staff has been lovingly working to put weight on this 8-year-old neutered American Bully mix dog.  As a result his coat has gotten pretty and glossy. He is still thin, but is looking better in that respect, too. You can meet him by calling to schedule an adoption appointment.  In the meantime, staff is giving him great care which he appreciates.  Especially at feeding time!  Because he is already neutered, he can go home the same day he is adopted. If you are willing to provide him with good food, love and a real home, consider adopting him. The shelter is full and open kennels are always needed for more incoming animals.

Adoption fees are $80 for dogs.  Cat adoption fees are $50. Cash or check only. Please be sure to take the exact amount with you.

The shelter routinely vaccinates all healthy appearing animals upon their arrival at the shelter and deworms them.  Any animals not already spayed/neutered must have the procedure done through the veterinary clinic that contracts with the county before that animal can be released from the clinic to the new family. By state law, animals old enough to be given a rabies vaccine, must have that vaccine done, as well.  The vaccine is given by the veterinary clinic staff at a separate cost to the adoptive family. 

Hold periods for every incoming animal vary for several reasons including, but not limited to, whether the animal came in from the Cumberland County area, or from the City of Crossville, which contracts with the county for its animal shelter services.  Check with the staff to verify the availability date of every animal for which you have an interest.

For more information on this pet, call the shelter at (931)484-8525. The shelter is open Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, Friday, and Saturday from 10am to 2pm. Closed Wednesday and Sunday and county observed holidays.

animal.description:
This friendly girl is Daisy - she's a 5-year-old Boxer mix weighing about 45 pounds. She is very sweet & loving, just wants to please her people & is calm and gentle. She definitely has a Boxer personality and likes to give hugs!

This girl has been through so much. Dumped by owners, she was surrendered to a kill shelter and left to die. She was out of time when one of our rescue partners pulled her but wasn't able to find a rescue for her right away. Our rescue partner has had her for several months and she has done great with most dogs big and small. However, she can be selective at times due to being attacked by another dog.

Daisy's major issue is regular inappropriate urination. Our rescue partner has done an abdominal Ultrasound to rule out a mass (which looked normal), bloodwork to rule out Cushings or Addisons (again normal). At this point the vet believes it is either Diabetes Insipidus or psychosomatic. She is currently on meds for diabetics insipidus (there is no test - either the meds work and that the diagnosis, or they don't).

Daisy is the sweetest dog and deserves to be able to run and play outside and nap on the couch. Unfortunately she isn't able to do that in the foster home with the other dog who attacked her. Instead, she has to be kept separated for her own safety. Daisy has so much love to give, she deserves a home of her own where she will feel safe & be loved.

Daisy is currently located in Eastern North Carolina. A meet and greet can be arranged for a serious adopter who understands what is involved and would be willing to work with her to overcome her medical issues. If you'd like to meet her, please fill out an application at www.ehrdogs.org & be sure to mention her name, DAISY GIO!

animal.description:
Sasha is a 7 year old Lab/Heeler mix who joined the C.A.R.E. Family after being rescued from death row at Animal Control. She was blind and suffering from a terrible skin infection. We immediately took her to see our veterinarian where she was diagnosed with allergies. Sasha was prescribed a once a day medication that she will need to continue to take at her new home. She definitely feels so much better now! Some of her hair loss may be permanent but we make sure to tell her how beautiful she is each and every day. Sasha's results from her bloodwork to check for any other underlying illnesses all came back great as well. :) 

Sasha is excited to meet her forever family! She is blind but she doesn't let that slow her down one bit.. She just relies a little more on her other senses to guide her and help her memorize new surroundings. This smart girl can sniff out a treat jar in no time! Sasha gets along well with other dogs and she would love to find a home with a nice fenced yard where she can enjoy some time outside with her new family. Sasha knows basic commands and a few fun tricks that she can not wait to show off for her new fanily!

You can meet Sasha in person at our adoption center located at 1328 West Sunshine St. Springfield MO. We are open Thursday, Friday, and Sat from 10am to 4pm. You can also submit a online dog adoption application at www.carerscue.org to be pre-approved to adopt Sasha. All C.A.R.E rescue dogs are fully vaccinated, heart-worm tested, spayed/neutered, and microchipped!

Our adoption fee is a minimum $100 tax deductible donation. All donations are used for rescue and medical care of animals in need. If you don't have room to take home a pet but want to support our efforts to save animals in need, please consider donating. We are not city or state funded and rely solely on private donations that allow us to continue saving lives.

To learn more about us or to give a lifesaving donation please visit http://www.carerescue.org

animal.description: Hi! My name is Nesti and I was rescued in Puerto Rico before arriving at the Big Dog Ranch & Rescue. I like to play with other dogs but I can sometimes be a little bit selective when it comes to who I choose to interact with. I would benefit from an experienced dog owner who can help me get out of my shell a little bit. I can be a little shy at times, but I've got a truly sweet soul and I'm just looking for people who can help me build my confidence. I would benefit from an experienced dog owner who can guide me through life. I think I could be happy in a busy or a quiet lifestyle but either would take some getting used to for me. I could benefit from some continued training, as I am not quite potty-trained yet, but I do love to go for long leashed walks and have picked up that skill very quickly so I think that I can get the hang of anything if you give me a little bit of time. animal.description:
Those eyes...that underbite...meet Freddie! 
This seven-year-old Shih Tzu is all about love. Hes super-affectionate, playful, happy and wants to make friends right away. 
Freddie sits for treats, and is extremely food motivated. Actually, dont tell Freddie, he could stand to lose a few pounds from all of that food motivation. ...but hes still perfectly adorable. He even does a cute little dance on his hind legs, and waves his front paws when hes very happy.
But as adorable as he is, Freddie is a challenge... one that requires an experienced owner, ideally an older couple or single... someone to help Freddie with his fears and insecurities and give him all the attention and love that he deserves. Freddie does not get along with other animals. He has separation anxiety. He will occasionally guard a possession... sometimes something as silly as a tissue. And Freddie can be vocal so he will not make a good neighbor for an apartment dweller.
Despite all of that, or maybe because of it, Freddie deserves love, empathy and the patience to look past his imperfections, see and enjoy the best in him, and give him a home where he will be forever cherished.
The biggest rewards come to those who make a commitment to a special guy like Freddie.
He is as lovable as he looks and is waiting to be a great best friend.

Maybe you are ready for Freddie?

My name is: Sparkle
Breed: American Pit Bull Terrier
Gender: Female - spayed
Color: White with brown near her eye
Size: 63 lbs
Approximate age: 1 year
Energy Level: average
Foster family says: Sparkle is a very patient girl who has waited for her forever family for a long time. She has so many stereotypes going against her that we can only think that's why she hasn't been adopted.

Sparkle is excellent with other dogs, cats & children big & small. She is crate trained, house trained, knows hand signals & is excellent on a leash. She is deaf & blind in one eye, she was born that way & has no 'startle' reflex, if you tap her while she is asleep she doesn't even flinch.

Sparkle is ready for you, her adoption fee is wavied to an approved home.

Please fill out an application at www.iRescueHomelessPets.org under the adopt tab to add Sparkle to your family forever.

We HIGHLY recommend you take your dog/puppy to formal obedience classes with a qualified trainer. This will help you and your dog/puppy learn and bond with each other.

While we do the best to determine the breed of our dogs, the majority are turned in as strays & we have only general appearance, coat type, size, ear type, tail & coat color to base breed on. It is always possible when adopting a puppy that it can dramatically change and look like another breed as it grows up.

Our fees are typically $75.00 for adult dogs & $150.00 for fully vetted puppies.

Fill out an application at https://form.jotform.com/40468849602159 to add this pet to your family forever.http://iRescueHomelessPets.org

animal.description:
MEET KITTY!

Kitty is a beautiful 3 year old girl looking for her furever home. It appears Kitty was a backyard dog, so she'll need a patient owner who understands this and work on Kitty's training. She is a friendly girl, but is cautious and timid at first. She needs an owner who will show her she can trust humans and she doesn't need to be scared anymore! Kitty can jump a 6 foot fence so she'll need a home without a doggy door, at least at first, and someone supervising her while she is outside. Since Kitty has been at the shelter, she has shown great improvement. She is easy to leash and walks very easily. She loves to sniff everything and when she comes back to the shelter, she likes to go to the play yard so she can get some more lovin' before she goes back in her kennel.

Kitty came in with another dog (Dragoon), and while she appears too scared at the shelter to play with Dragoon she is friendly with this dog. If you are interested in Kitty and have dogs currently a meet and greet is strongly encouraged. Kitty has a lot of life left to live and a lot of love to give! She needs someone to step up and show her how great her life can be! Are you that person? Come meet Kitty today!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in its possession. To visit with this pup, please make an appointment here: https://mcaccappointments.as.me/adopt. NOTE: People who sign up for these appointments often no-show. We have been told that you can go straight to the shelter and let them know you are there to meet this particular dog. From what we understand, the shelter will squeeze you in except between 12-3PM and near the 6PM closing time. (Please know this is not a guarantee). If the dog is at risk, please ask for a supervisor to meet that particular dog. We hope your adoption process is smooth and full of happiness!

This amazing pup is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4480645

*Please Note: This animal is courtesy posted for the Maricopa County Shelter; UNDERDOG RESCUE DOES NOT HAVE THIS DOG. MCACC is located at 2500 S. 27th Avenue, Phoenix. Different adoption fees/policy may apply. Please visit MCACC's website http://www.maricopa.gov/pets/locations.aspx for hours. You may also wish to call 602-506-7387 (PETS) and provide the animal's A# above to verify is still available.

Jesse is a sweet dober boy, around 6 years old. He was abandoned at a dog park in 2019, and we stepped up to give him a chance at a better life. He had ear, skin, and eye infections but he's all fixed up now! Soon after being rescued, Jesse was adopted by a wonderful man. Sadly, his daddy is terminally ill and Jesse finds himself with the rescue and once again, searching for a home. He is a sad, confused baby right now.

He would do best in either a household on his own, or with a female dog his size. This gentle and loving boy would love a place to call his own. Jesse is your typical Velcro-Dobie, he loves being with his people and getting his fabulous ears scratched.

For more information on Jesse, or to set up a meet and greet, please call or text Ginny at 954-295-7536 between 7pm and 10pm. You can also fill out an application on our website at www.doberescue.net.

I am a spunky 8 year old female Shih Tzu. I'm a semi toothless DIVA. I weigh around 13 lbs so I'm not very big. I love going for walks with my foster mommy and she thinks it is funny when I playfully tug on my leash as we head out the door. I'm still working on my house training but once I get relaxed in my new home and you have a little patience with me I should be fine. I'm great with other dogs and my mommy thinks that based on my personality I would be OK around cats too. I don't know. I don't think I've ever met a cat so that remains to be seen. For the most part I'm pretty good with anything that comes my way. Now that I feel better I'm a much happier girl and just thankful to be alive.
If you think you'd be interested in becoming my forever family please send an email to fureverangels@aol..com and request an application. I'm really looking forward, for the first time in my life, to see what great things lie ahead for me.

animal.description:
MoMo Jokomo   
(#A1308 Buisy) 8 month old pit bull

This little guy was pulled from MAS after a 2nd plea was issued for him. He had a tie out wrapped around his abdomen and penis, which caused his prepuce to start dying. He had surgery to repair this and while his penis looks slightly different, it does not impair him in any way.  He urinates like normal and is not disfigured. 

When he first arrived at his foster mom’s, he was fearful of walking outside by himself and coward when he had an accident. He has overcome that. He is just a baby and still figuring everything out. He is currently working on crate training, potty training, not jumping and sitting. He is extremely loving, gentle, has the most beautiful eyes that speak to your soul, loves any attention and especially loves to have his face held in your hands and his belly rubbed. He gets along with other dogs, but sometimes does not know his limits and does not take correction from other dogs. He is eager to learn.

animal.description:
Tucker will be joining us on 10/24...he will be fostering in the Chicago area. He is approximately 8 years old, tested very well with other dogs at the shelter but is NOT good with cats. Please check back in soon for updates on Tucker!! 11/2: Tucker arrived at his foster home and is getting all acquainted and adjusted to foster home life :) He gets along great with his foster furbrother Ernie and has discovered that lounging on the couch is one of his new favorite things. He saw the vet to get his eyes checked out...the vet feels that he is most likely completely blind in his right eye. He has a detached lens and atrophy of the retina. He also has a cataract in his left eye so sees somewhat limited in that eye. The vet also says that it looks like he had an abnormal reaction to dilating drops in that left eye at some point which left his pupil permanently dilated. It doesn't seem to bother him and he gets around great so his eyes have likely been this way for a while. 12/15 UPDATE from Tucker (now known as Bert)'s foster mom....Bert has settled right in to our household. He's a laid back guy and, while he loves going for walks, he seems to really like hanging out with the family and being a total couch potato. He isn't a demanding dog in terms of exercise. He is a real love bug and wants to crawl right into your lap (all 78 lbs!) and snuggle.
He does have vision problems, which is apparent when you look into his eyes, but he gets around just fine. He seems to see pretty well, even at night. He has no trouble crawling into bed in the dead of night. I have seen him bump into things on his right side (his worse eye apparently) but he will chase a ball fine and I've seen him chase squirrels as well.
He isn't picky with his food, he'll eat whatever you put down in front of him. But he is kind of itchy, so we are trying out a grain free diet to see if this will help.
He walks well on a leash, but does have problems when another dog crosses our path. He will bark and pull. We are doing some training with a gentle leader to see if this will solve this issue.
Bert requires some warming up to other dogs, but he gets along great with our young male Ernie. They frequently cuddle together on the couch.
Bert would be a great dog for a family who wants a more laid back, easy going boxer.
animal.name: Tucker aka Bert

animal.description: This ADORABLE petite girl is Vanessa and she arrived at her North Carolina foster home and is getting settled in. Vanessa was a little snarky with high energy dogs that she was temperament tested with at the shelter but with a foster offer for her who understands that, we were able to pull her into the rescue. She is not spayed yet, which could be part of the behavior and/or she may not be feeling the best due to testing positive for heartworm disease, plus she just looked terrified in her intake pictures. One look at that scared face and we just knew we had to help her. Vanessa has started on pretreatment medications and she will be seeing the vet very soon to get all checked over. FROM HER FOSTER MOM: Vanessa is doing great. She's in her shutdown period. She's learned the routine fast. There's never a peep out of her in the crate. Matter of fact she hasn't even barked one time. She did have an accident in her crate last night after she was out a hour earlier and pooped outside. I am pretty sure it was because we overfed her at dinner time. So totally our fault. Lesson learned. She's so sweet. All she wants to do is be loved on. She's going to be a total love bug. She's just happy as she can be though! She's not scared now. She just smiles and wags that tail!2/2/21: Vanessa is learning the ropes at her forever foster home and is feeling a little better about things. She is currently undergoing heartworm treatment.

animal.description:
Billie
Male
Terrier mix
Born 2019

Contact Kate at kmolsbe@gmail.com for more information about Billie.

You have heard the phrase "Looks can be deceiving"?  Well, Billie is the perfect example of that phrase!  Looking at his pictures below, you would say he is shy and fearful, telling you "please don't look at me"!!  Get him in his foster home environment and he is a completely different dog - playful, scampering around with his new buddy Winston, getting into mischief at every opportunity - a happy little guy!  Billie, as well as his brother Willie, were extremely shy of humans when they came to NMAF from a rural shelter where they found themselves after being picked up as strays.  We have no other information beyond that.  It took time for them to adjust, Billie coming along faster.  Once they were separated into different foster homes, both have made great progress in dog and human socialization.  Billie's foster mom calls him a little hooligan - he is always looking for some form of mischief to get into!  Leave your shoes out - Billie will remind you not to...  Have your sweater on a chair, he just might claim it for his own!  Billie is a young pup and still has that puppy energy and inquisitiveness.  He is still shy of new people but, given time and another young playful dog in his Furever Home, he will come around.  Super smart and cute as a button, whatever Terrier mix he is, is NOT hypoallergenic, so please don't inquire if you are seeking a hypoallergenic dog.  Billie should not be an only dog and would do best with playful doggy playmates near his own size.  He will take time and patience to adjust to new surroundings, and training/coaching will be provided.  He is neutered, up-to-date on shots, and microchipped.

Billie would do best in a home without young children as he is skittish and shy at first.  His doggy brother(s) or sister(s) will show him the way to adjust and help his family see what a bright and happy little guy he is.  Trust is one of the hardest things to build in a dog, but Billie has shown he can do it and will continue to improve in the right environment.  NMAF can also offer professional trainer options to help with socialization & training.

If you are interested in meeting Billie, please complete an application, found at www.nmaf.org/adopt/adoption-application, and email it to dogs@nmaf.org.  There is no commitment or guarantee for adoption, but your application allows for screening before setting up a meet & greet with his foster.

Because home visits are required, NMAF dogs cannot be adopted out of the greater Albuquerque / Santa Fe area.

Adoption Clinic Location:  PetSmart - Academy & Wyoming, Saturdays, 10:00 a.m. - 1:00 p.m. - Currently Suspended

Please visit our website at www.nmaf.org for more information.

animal.description:
***Sunshine is only available through our Foster to Adopt Program***


Hi, Sunshine here! I am just an itty bitty little, 10 year old chihuahua/mix. 

I was a stray dog in Alabama, so I am leery of people and other dogs. I am finally learning to trust people again. I am quiet, well mannered, and am NOT a barker. I'm learning all about living in a house and I'm doing great. Foster Mom says I'm just about house trained so she's very proud of me. I'm working really hard and I know I'll master it soon! I had 13 bad teeth removed, so I am finally enjoying eating again. I am also heartworm positive and am in the middle of my treatment. I'm doing great and can't wait to get a negative test result. The treatment is covered by Warrior Dog Rescue. 

I would love to find a home with adults who will give me love and patience, so that my award-winning personality can shine through. I will need a fairly quiet, low-key home, especially during my heartworm treatment, to promote healing. I know I could make a wonderful addition to someone's family. Could that be yours?



FOSTER TO ADOPT:
Sunshine is in the middle of her Heartworm treatment. After her treatment is completed, she will be tested periodically and will wait for a negative test result which can take 2-9 months after treatment. During these months, she will need to make sure her heart rate is not elevated due to high energy play or exercise. Sunshine is only available through the Foster to Adopt Program at this time. The commitment will be for an adoption but will be fostering until she is cleared with a negative Heartworm test result. All of the medical expenses will be paid for by the rescue while she is in a foster to adopt home. Food, kennel, grooming and other supplies will be provided by the foster in the foster to adopt program. 


--------------------------------------------



All our Warrior Dogs will have all age appropriate medical care and vaccines, a microchip, and spay/neuter before adoption unless age is a factor with a puppy younger than 6-12 months at the time of adoption. If that is the case, the spay/neuter will be covered in the adoption fee and the owner will be responsible to have the procedure completed at a Warrior Dog Rescue Veterinarian at the appropriate time.

Please note that the majority of our dogs in rescue are from shelters where they have been found as strays or abandoned. Their breed description is based on our very best educated guess based on physical characteristics and their dispositions. If they came to our rescue as an owner surrender, the breed description will be listed as provided by the previous owner.

Adoption Fee - $400

To apply for this pup, please submit an Adoption Application at http://warriordogrescue.com/adopt/adoption-application/

animal.description:
Cruiser is about 2-3 years old, Shephard mix weighing about 45lbs. Cruiser found himself on the euthanasia list at a kill shelter in Houston TX after he was found wandering around. A group of people saved him. His owner was later tracked down and they said they didn't want him and gave no reason why. Cruiser is very sweet and after he warms up loves his humans. Cruiser is in a foster home in the Puyallup, WA area and we've learned more about him. He is definitely an alpha dog which means he needs to be the leader as he is dominant. He has a very HIGH prey drive, so no smaller dogs and NO cats. He okay with dogs his own size, but need slow and patient introductions.  When he does not want to do something- like putting a harness on him- he will let you know by growling or raising his lip. He has not shown any aggression towards his foster mom, but is able to tell her when he's not a fan of something. We think kids would over stimulated him so we are recommending a home with no kids. 
So those are some quirks that he has so let us tell you about Cruiser's very positive traits. He is wicked smart and very food motivated. His foster mom is working with him on clicker training. He loves humans and is extremely eager to please. He walks well on leash, but he is very strong. His ideal home would be very active and giving him a place to run and play. His foster mom describes him as a very loving and sweet dog who deserves the right home. He will need continued training and patience. . We would love to find him a home that won't abandon him as he deserves a family of his own.

Please fill out an adoption application if you are interested in Cruiser 
https://heartoftheunderdog.org/adoption-application

So those are some quirks that he has so let us tell you about Cruiser's very positive traits. He is wicked smart and very food motivated. His foster mom is working with him on clicker training. He loves humans and is extremely eager to please. He walks well on leash, but he is very strong. His ideal home would be very active and giving him a place to run and play. His foster mom describes him as a very loving and sweet dog who deserves the right home. He will need continued training and patience. . We would love to find him a home that won't abandon him as he deserves a family of his own.

animal.description:
** ADOPTED - We can no longer accept applications for Chevy.


With his stunning looks and charismatic personality, Chevy won over the hearts of everyone at the vet hospital where he was recovering from surgery.  He didn't have a family to go home with but within a few days, he was welcomed into a foster home with one of the veterinarians who cared for him.    

We estimate Chevy’s age to be around 4 years old.  He currently weighs 95 pounds, is already neutered, and tested negative for heartworm disease a few weeks ago. He’s been taking monthly preventatives. 

Chevy is housebroken, crate trained, loves being with people, and is great with other dogs.  He sleeps right through the night, doesn’t counter surf, is very respectful and eager to please. 

Chevy is an awesome companion and a true joy to spend time with! 

His foster mom shared: 

“He is the biggest, cuddliest love bug who wants to sit on your lap and hang out with you.  Super dog skills, very sociable and amicable with other dogs and people. Doesn’t bark but loves to “talk”. He does the Shepherd talking & it’s very cute. (Video coming soon).  Gives very gentle kisses and takes treats so nicely from your hand.” 

We do not provide DNA testing which is the only way to know with certainty which breeds are in his genetic background. Our best guess is that he is a  Shepherd mix.  

Highlights about Chevy:
- Great with other dogs 
- Crate trained
- House broken
- Curious & friendly 
- Easy going personality
- Loves people 
- Up-to-date on vaccines
- Has been neutered 
- Heartworm negative- tested in October  

Our adoption fee is $375 which includes age appropriate vaccines (such as Distemper, Bordetella, Parvo, Rabies), neutering, worming, micro-chipping, and health exam. Discount vouchers for training, grooming and similar dog related products and services are provided.

animal.description:
Meet Milady!
Milady arrived to the Benton-Franklin Humane Society all the way from Merced, California to find a new lease on life. She came to us with a split tongue and a clearly painful hind end. Thankfully, our lovely medical partners have created a long-term management plan that has been working so well that today, we would never know she had these challenges!
Milady exhibits many characteristics of a Malinois, and breed experience is preferred but not required. She is an incredibly smart girl who needs an owner ready to keep her brain engaged. Milady has really blossomed during her stay with us, and we can't stress enough how silly this girl is once she feels comfortable! Milady enjoys prancing along and stopping to sniff the flowers on long walks, the occasional zoomies, and being told she's a good doggo. I mean, who wouldn't?
Milady will need something specific to be successful in having the best life she possibly can. After all, she deserves just that, doesn't she? Milady would do best as an only-pet, and will require a home with older, dog savvy children or an adult-only residence.
Milady has a consult prior to her adoption, so give us a call at 509-374-4235 to learn more about her! Primary Color: Black Secondary Color: Tan Weight: 67.4lbs Age: 5yrs 3mths 3wks Animal has been Spayed
