animal.description:
PLEASE FILL OUT AN APPLICATION FOR ADOPTION!  Please do not call the shelter, until you have completed an application and are ready to make an apt for a meet and greet. Inquiries will not be answered at this time.

Mongo is an older fella that came to us in very poor condition.  He was mangy, emaciated and have wounds all over his body.  We estimate him to be around 5-6 years old.  Life has not been kind to this boy, and he really has never had real love until reaching our shelter.  He has run as a wild dog most of his life.  Upon coming into our facility he really wanted nothing to do with people and did not trust us at all.  He has many skin allergies and requires to be on a special diet that can be a bit costly per month.  We will supply you with the first bit of food for him.  He gets sore from time to time and will need an anti-inflammatory to help ease the pain some days.  Mongo has really decided to trust us and he wants nothing more now than to be with his person.  He does well with female dogs, he does not really interact with them but he can co-exist peacefully.  No small animals or male dogs for Mongo.  If you think you have the right home for Mongo please fill out an application.  We truly want him to go to the best home that can afford his medical/food needs on a monthly basis.  We know he can show you his big heart if given the chance.  (His favorite thing to do is sleep on warm fuzzy blankets on his bed) He LOVES naps! Please research POSITIVE training techniques before applying to adopt. We care very much about your application answers and they are reviewed for completeness and the best match.   Please fill out an application on the included link: https://threerivershs.org/adoption-app-2/

The adoption fee of $175 includes spay/neuter, current vaccines, microchip, free vet visit, 30 days of pet health insurance, puppy book, and engraved ID tag.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Please Click Here to Fill Out an Online Adoption Application!
Dime is a very calm and good boy, but he is fearful and is NOT the type of dog that will sit in your lap!
He LOVES other dogs, especially smaller dogs!
Dime has gone through a lot, and will benefit from a foster home, or an understanding furever home!

Update 10/29/2020:

Dime is officially letting us touch him, and is giving us kisses in exchange for some meat and cheese (high value treats like raw meat work great)
Dime follows us around like a shadow, and is getting much better about understanding that he only needs to be kenneled when he eats (or when he wants to of course) and can roam around with us.
Dime is still getting used to his potty training but he is doing MUCH better!!
He is also showing interest in playing with toys, but he did end up guarding a squeeky toy from another small male dog (not unusaul, but something we would want to bring up!)
Dime seems to adore medium female dogs, or non dominant male dogs. He is finally opened up enough to start playing with them at times!
Good boy, Dime!!!

Update 01/14/2021:

Dime has had many visitors, but nobody that has understood that Dime will not be a companion animal right away. He will need LOTS of time to decompress at his new home, and to get to know you. He is not the type of dog to run up for affection, or to take out on walks just yet. (he bites through and will slip his leash/harness so please believe us and don't risk it)

He will need to be in a home that understands that he will need a companion animal, preferably a small or medium sized female, to help him come out of his shell.
He is fine with cats and all other critters from what we have seen!
Dime will NOT be good in a home with kids under 13, due to being a bite risk if he is cornered.

He is curious, adventurous, loves to run and play and gets along with most of the dogs he has met. He will do well with a buddy he can learn and mentor from and will benefit from a huge yard or acreage to run and play under guidance. He also needs an adopter who will commit to working with a professional trainer or who is a dog trainer who works in Postive reinforcement.

RIDER is a herding dog. He needs a child-free home and would do best being a pet but living on acreage and being able to accompany someone everyday-OR be adopted into an adult only home with super active hikers and outdoor types with trips to the beach and woods frequently and 2-3 miles or more a day of daily exercise and he must have a dog Buddy. Rider is in foster care and walks several miles a day. Rider is in more of a city area at this moment and the city is stress for him, so we are seeking an urban setting, acreage, and Very active owners familiar with this breed who already own an active younger dog to be Riders BFF.

Rider is being fed a Human Grade and Raw Canine diet. We educate our adopters in canine and species-specific nutrition. Rider is neutered, up to date and ready for his forever home. You can read about our feeding and care philosophy and learn more on our website-http://rompinpawsrescue.rescuegroups.org/. you can apply to adopt here as well.

To fill out an application to adopt Please use this link, You will need a computer to complete as cell phones will drop the application

http://rompinpawsrescue.rescuegroups.org/forms/

The site will ask you to create a password and will send you an email. For ease of use, just use the password they create for you and save that password. This will ensure you have access and can fill out the application.

animal.description:
Deke ACCT-A-65686
Intake:Stray

Bio from Foster: 
Deke is a young, medium sized pit mix that really loves other dogs. He has been with his current fosters since mid-March 2020 and is looking for his forever family.

Deke can be cautious of strangers and is looking for adopters who will continue to help him overcome his fear of meeting new people. His forever family should be experienced dog owners with other dog(s) in the household to help him acclimate to a new family. Deke recently completed 8 weeks of positive reinforcement professional training to help him with his confidence.

Deke really enjoys going on walks and being around other dogs. He loves to romp around the yard with his friends and can often be found sunbathing while his foster parents are working. His foster parents consider Deke to be medium energy. He does have some "zoomies during the day but can also settle down to cuddle on the couch with his humans.

Deke would do best in a low trafficked household and without young children or cats. He is potty-trained and crate trained. It took Deke about 4 months in his current foster home to not howl in his crate while being left alone as he did have some initial separation anxiety. While it was not destructive behavior, potential adopters should be aware of the noise level for neighbor purposes if their house is connected to others.
 

Please reach out to his fosters at KandPFosters@gmail.com for additional information regarding Deke and a questionnaire for potential adopters.


This animal is currently available from foster care through ACCT Philly's Adoptions Programs. This animal is not onsite. If the foster has not listed a personal email, contact foster@acctphilly.org to be put in touch with the foster. 

We encourage you to visit our shelter during our adoption hours to view our complete selection of available animals. In preparation for your visit, please make sure to visit http://www.acctphilly.org/adopt/ to review our adoption requirements, hours of operation, upcoming events, and more! 

Is this your missing pet? If you believe so, please make sure to follow the instructions listed at http://www.acctphilly.org/lostpet/ so that we can make sure that you are reunited as soon as possible!

Wed like to shine a light on a couple of adult large breed dogs dear to us with another small, local rescue Boxers Mutts & Wiggle Butts Rescue Please help share their dogs, give them a follow, and show them some of the amazing support you show us.

First, we have Sookie! We first learned of Sookie 8 months ago. A property owner saw her and another dog thrown out of a pickup truck abandoned in the orchards. The man admitted to shooting at her several times. She was skin and bones when found. Unable to take her in ourselves, we offered to sponsor her food during her time in rescue. At the time we had donations from The Honest Kitchen and that was the best food to help her to gain weight and get back to being healthy.
@boxersmuttsnwigglebuttsrescue have done an amazing job getting Sookie healthy and happy again. Sookie is a boxer, 3.5 years old. She LOVES belly rubs but shes no couch potato, shed prefer being your running buddy. She knows sit, wait, come, crate and potty trained. Shes great with kids and is gentle with toys. Reach out to her rescue to learn more! 
Get to know Sookie and we are sure she will win your heart. Here is a little bit about her: 
* LOVES people, adults and kids 
* very high energy 
* needs to be the only dog. Not dog/cat friendly * knows sit
* knows wait
* comes when called
* crate trained
* is soft with toys and learning fetch 
* Loooves belly rubs

animal.description:
Isn't Earl absolutely adorable with his stubby snoot and wiry coat? He is a total cuddle bug with a great personality and just wants to be your best friend! He can be interactive, talkative and energetic but also settles down and relaxes very nicely. This well-rounded, friendly fellow is a great listener and sits beautifully for treats (as you'll see on our Furry Friend Fridays segment!) He loves to catch them in his mouth!

We rescued Earl from one of the local municipal shelters. He had some hair loss on the neck which was probably from a collar being too tight. His teeth are quite ground down which can happen for many different reasons. We assume that he was probably not in the most loving and attentive of homes.

Earl's only fault is being dog reactive so he will need to be in a home preferably without any other pets. Other than that, he really is the perfect companion for any family! Let's find Earl the perfect fur-ever home that he deserves!

My adoption fee of $200 includes my up-to-date vaccinations, microchip, deworming, and I come home spayed/neutered. I even started on my monthly flea and heartworm preventatives - what more could you ask for? 

If you're interested in adopting me, please fill out an application on our website, PawmettoLifeline.org. Feel free to check out more of my friends or more information on PawmettoLifeline.org. The Pawmetto Lifeline Adoptions Department is open to all approved applicants on a walk-in basis from Tuesdays through Saturdays from 12pm to 6pm. Our last meet and greet is at 5:30pm. We are closed on Sundays and Mondays. We can't wait for you to find your match! Could I be the one for you?

Ridge is a new arrival.     She arrived as seen in last the photos.   We are working with her now and she is adapting well to learning house manners and about socialization.   Oh and eating on a regular basis.   She is now fully recovered and can move on to to a new home. 
..
She was a cruelty case and the cut on her leg is from a tie out cable.    We will be updating her photos as she completes her transformation.  (photo 1) 

   She does have an issue with eating food too quickly, and this might take months to undo.   Her new humans must be patient and willing to bring out the best in her. 

Yes she has a ridge on her back.  Previous owners claimed her as being a phu quoc.   However, we doubt that.   Likely a  RR x Lab.   

Arrival weight 24 lb we expect her to be around 40 when healthy.  She seems to have a high prey drive with smaller animals.  And would likely will be dog selective.  She is best suited for someone familiar with dog obedience training.  Not ideal for a first time dog owner. 

Adoption info and applications are at www.hollowcreekfarm.org

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting or meeting any of our animals available for adoption you will need to FILL OUT AN ONLINE ADOPTION APPLICATION ON OUR WEBSITE FIRST. Due to the volume of interest in our animals and the convenience we now offer of applying online for adoption, we are no longer able to reply to messages sent through our Petfinder page. MESSAGES RECEIVED THROUGH PETFINDER WILL GO UNANSWERED.
Copy and paste this URL link to learn everything you need to know about the adoption process and to fill out the application.
https://www.grandstrandhumanesociety.com/adopt/ 

Meet Promise
She is the definition of strength, perseverance and hope. Promise came in 3 weeks ago with reports of having been accidentally shut in a car door and gradually losing the ability to use her back legs. We knew that Promise would need lots of special care and around the clock attention so we reached out to several animal rescue organizations in hopes that a smaller group would have more time and resources to dedicate to this very special girl. Unfortunately no other groups had room for Promise, so she's staying with us. She told us she loves being a beach babe anyways...
The first thing that Promise needed was a wheelchair. The kind-hearted daughter of one of our amazing volunteers ordered one immediately!! Because x-rays showed no abnormalities, we were told we needed to have a CT scan done to see what kind of damage there was. That was done this past weekend and it looks like Promise has an inoperable spinal lesion spanning her T12 and L2 vertebrae.
Our next steps are further confirmation testing, and discussing rehabilitation options. We refuse to lose hope that one day she could walk again.
Promise greets every day with a huge smile, tons of kisses and plenty of tail wags. She is such an inspiration to all of us at GSHS and we are so fortunate that she came into our lives.

animal.description:
I am Midnite. I am a sweet gentleman, 10 years old. I am approximately 15 #. My previous family could not keep me so they decided the best place for me was JRs Pups-N-Stuff. Boy were they right!! I am currently in a home with lots of other dogs that don't bother me, and cats. Also I now have a bunch of little children that want to snuggle with me. I love them all. I am house trained and I really don't need to be in a crate, I don't cause any trouble. I only bark when necessary never just because. 
I am a little dog so it does take a little bit for me to trust and warm up; I will bark and growl when someone new arrives. Give me a little space and time and I will warm up.
If you are looking for a great little dog I am your guy.

Adoption fee: $350
 
Adoption fees for all dogs/puppies include a $50 refundable training deposit. Complete your basic training program and provide a copy of the certificate within 4 months (120 days) of adoption and we will refund $50 of the original adoption fee.
 
All dogs/puppies have been fully vetted including spay/neuter, micro-chipping, worming, heartworm testing and preventative treatment, flea/tick preventative, and all required age appropriate vaccinations. As required by Wisconsin Act 90, all dogs will have received a veterinarian exam (CVI) within the past 30 days.
 
Our adoption process requires the submission of an application. Applications and Adoption Rules can be found on our website, on the "HOW TO ADOPT" tab at JRsPupsNStuff.org. Upon receipt of the completed application, we will process the application including: contact with your veterinarian and completion of a home visit. Please be sure to include the contact information for your vet as we will call. If your vet requires an information release, please be sure to contact them as soon as you submit your application. We are a group of volunteers with families and jobs, so please be patient and allow a few days for our response.
 
JR's Pups-N-Stuff Dog Sellers License 270089-DS

animal.description:
Meet Reba! This sweet 2 year old shepherd mix girl is looking for a forever home! Reba is an energetic (bouncy), sweet girl. She gets very excited when her foster parents get home from work but quickly settles into the snuggle bug that she truly is. She is fully crate trained and recently has been left home alone out of her crate (8+ hours) with no issues (no chewing/destruction, no potty accidents)!

Reba is a really smart gal and has high potential for being trained - whether that's basic or agility she would excel; she is highly treat motivated. She already knows sit, lay down and is working on stay. She needs work on come and her leash manners. 

Likes: Squirrels, looking out windows, destroying chew toys, romping in the snow, snuggling, wearing pajamas, grandmas + great grandmas, cheese, & other dogs. 

Dislikes: Vacuum cleaners, water, squirrels  

I would recommend she goes to a family with no kids or dog savvy, dog confident children. She is high energy which sometimes manifests as mouthy. Mouthy + high speed boinks = no good for small children.

animal.description:
***Mitzi is in a loving foster home in the Pennington, NJ area***

Mitzi and her friend, Molly, found themselves in need of a new home after their former owner passed away unexpectedly. Scared and facing an uncertain future, due mainly because of their age, Mitzi and Molly had to be wondering if their time on this earth was also about to come to an end. After receiving a call seeking help for these senior ladies, we gladly offered them a place to stay.

We were told that Mitzi was timid and we found her to be so when she first arrived. She often scurries away from people who approached her, generally retreating to her bed. Once Mitzi gives up the game of chase, she simply cowards down in her bed and allows herself to be picked up. Over the last week, Mitzi has started to feel comfortable with us and is becoming less resistant in her interaction with our staff and loves to snuggle once she feels safe in your arms and will even give you a rare kiss! Mitzi needs a calm home and would be great for a senior/retired person. She does walk well on a leash, may have some house training (but please be prepared to offer house training) and is basically a quiet, calm little girl who is truly yearning for someone in which she can feel safe and loved.

Mitzi was spay prior to coming to our rescue. We've updated her vaccinations, administered de-wormers and resumed her monthly preventatives. Mitzi also tested negative for heartworms during her recent vet examination. Mitzi appeared to have a slight urinary infection when she arrived and was treated with antibiotics. Other than the normal age-related ailments, Mitzi appears to be in good health for a 10 year old dog.

If you can provide a calm, secure and safe home for Mitzi, please submit an application at socorescue.com

Molly and Mitzi have been together most of their lives. We thought that they needed to stay together but after being in a foster home for over a month, we noticed that they would be fine seperated. Senior dog rescues are also welcome.

Molly and her friend, Mitzi, found themselves in need of a new home after their former owner passed away unexpectedly. Scared and facing an uncertain future, due mainly because of their age, these senior girls had to be wondering if their time on this earth was also about to come to an end. After receiving a call seeking help for these senior ladies, we gladly offered them a place to stay.

We can tell that Molly had to be a very friendly, outgoing girl in her younger days. Now a senior of 13 years, Molly still yearns for human contact but at a much slower pace. She's obviously accustomed to being handled but care needs to be taken when and if picking her up. She would be excellent as a companion for a retired/senior person who desires a very low-keyed dog.

Molly was spay prior to coming to our rescue. We've updated her vaccinations, administered de-wormers and resumed her monthly preventatives. Molly also tested negative for heartworms during her recent vet examination. Other than a slight ear infection, which has now been treated, and the "normal" age ailments,, Molly appears to be in great health for a dog her age.

If you can provide a calm, secure and safe home for Molly, please submit an application at socorescue.com

animal.description:
Unlike her namesake, Garbo would never say “I want to be alone.” Garbo is a one year old girl who loves running and playing with her doggy friends and then snuggling up to her humans. At her boarding facility, Garbo is known as a “love bug.”

Garbo loves playing with other dogs, and especially enjoys other dogs who love to run and play. Garbo likes to be around her humans or other dogs, but if that’s not an option, she will settle down nicely.

Garbo is mostly an English Setter and has a fair amount of the prey drive English Setters are known for. Those who have been around Garbo think she may be mixed with a dash of Border Collie. She may be OK with cats, but would need supervision and slow acclimation in a home with cats to make sure.

Garbo needs all the things that an active young dog needs – lots of people time and training, plenty of exercise and stimulation, and either an active dog in the home or a person that is mostly home and who will make sure that she is socialized regularly with other dogs. She also needs a securely fenced yard with a 6’ fence to keep her safe. We’ve not had Izzy in a home with children and she is very active so she is only a candidate for homes with children 7+ years of age.

If Garbo has one fault, it is loving her food too much to share. Although she never resource-guards toys, she does guard her food. Food guarding is not uncommon in rescued dogs and is an issue that can be worked with, and sometimes eliminated.

Garbo is crate-trained and appears to be house trained. She has basic obedience training, but is a willing student who needs to learn more. She is fully vetted and ready for a foster-to-adopt or adoptive home. Currently, Garbo is in a boarding facility near Salt Lake City. For more about adopting from SWESR, see http://www.swesr.org/Apply-to-Adopt.html



For an application to adopt or for more information about Southwest English Setter Rescue including our adoption requirements and transport availability, please go to http://www.swesr.org/. Please call us at 214-997-3885 if you have any questions.

animal.description:
Welcome to our newest baby Bonsai!
Bonsai was dumped by a local breeder because he is special needs. Luckily our vet called us and asked us to take him in. After a visit to the neurologist, it was discovered that he has Cerebellar Hypoplasia, which is a disease that denotes an inadequate development of the cerebellum. The cerebellum in dogs is a section of the brainstem largely responsible for modulating motor impulses. This will be something that can improve over time with lots of love, rehab, dedication and care, but not cured. 

He is not available for adoption yet but we are accepting applications! Please download our app and send it to adoptions@reversedrescue.com if you are interested.

animal.description:
Meet Theta! Theta is the possible mom, or protective sibling of the greek group. She is about 3 years old, and she is very timid and sweet. When Theta first came to rescue with her other family members she was petrified, and tried to bite anyone that picked her up. She has flourished in her foster home, but is still quiet, and very sweet. She would be okay as an only dog, but she also gets along well with others. She's very protective over her family members, and snuggles with them often. She has just started playing with toys some, and she is getting more and more friendlier every day. She would do fine with older children, but I wouldn't put her with a toddler at least long term. She might be fine I just can't say for sure. She loves treats, and loves to be scratched, but is not a fan of baths. Theta was rescued with her siblings or kids when her former owners dumped her in the middle of a busy park during the day. She goes outside well, but she will definitely need work on house training, and she can't walk on a leash well so she needs a house with a secured yard. If you're interested in meeting Theta please go to our website and complete/submit an application, and we promise to take it from there. Please allow 1-2 weeks for us to process your application, but know we are hard at work on it. Our applications can be found on our website www.okwestierescue.com
*MUST HAVE SECURED FENCED IN YARD

NOTE: You must complete and submit an application and be approved to adopt prior to being able to meet the dog. The requested tax-deductible adoption donation is $400 for our puppies, $300 for up to age 7 and $150 for ages 8 and older.
We do not ship our pets. Be prepared to travel to Tulsa, OK, or Oklahoma City, OK, or the location where this dog is fostered to pick up your dog in person if your application is approved. Once you are approved, you may adopt any of our dogs that is a good fit. 
We are a non-profit organization that spends our adoption fees and donations on vaccinations, surgeries, various medical tests, medicines, food and supplies needed by our dogs. Our fees do not cover the overall expenses incurred by the care of our dogs, but they do help defray the costs involved. We thank you for your support. 

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always try to select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dog’s needs and try to find the best match for both dog and human. 
We leave a dog’s profile online until either it has been adopted, has received several applications, or is not able to be adopted for some reason.

animal.description:
Hi guys!

Baxter here, what's up?

I'm a boxer mix and I think I'm kinda handsome, don't you??

All I can say is that I'm a very lucky boy.  You see, I was scheduled for euthanasia twice and spared both times.  Can you believe that??  Due to some kind of divine intervention, a mistake was made by a sheriff's deputy.  When the city received a boarding bill for me, they notified the sheriff and the mistake was uncovered.  Not one person involved, including the vet and vet technician had the heart to end my life. 

The loving peeps at Lucies agreed to bring me to their rescue.  On the way there, I was very quiet cuz I was kinda scared.  The ladies stopped to get something to eat for themselves.  Being the sweet ladies that they are, they offered me some of their bacon and cheese covered fries, minus the bacon and cheese.  Really ladies...a plain fry??  Come on now, bring on the bacon and cheese!  Yay! Yum, yum, yum...that was the best food I have eaten - absolute heaven on earth!

Anyway, I've been here awhile and learned lots of new and fun things.  I can walk with a leash and stay in my crate when needed.  I love to run and romp and play.  I am very well mannered as well.

No stubborn bones in this canine body!  Won't you give me a chance?  I'd love to have a family of my very own.  Cheese and bacon covered fries are always good too ;)

*** We strive to ensure our dogs are going to a safe, loving and caring home. Phone interviews are required for all adoptions****

animal.description:
Hi I’m Winnie and I’m looking for a very special hooman!

I absolutely love people, but people haven’t always been so nice to me. My first owner turned out to be like the step mom in Cinderella..except worse. You see I loved my owner and I was such a good girl so I was really confused and heartbroken when my owner tied me to a stop sign on the side of a rural road and drove off without me. I was very pregnant at the time and underweight. I waited there for 4 long days in the southern heat wondering when they’d come back for me. Luckily there was a nearby business that would bring me meals everyday until animal control came and picked me up. 

I came to NY and gave birth to my babies. I was a good mama and took such great care of them. Now I’m ready to get my happily ever after.

I’m a 4 year old pitty mix with a heart of gold. Despite all I’ve been through I’m a VERY sweet girl with so much love to give.  I’m a homebody and prefer not to go out in public. I get too stimulated seeing other dogs so I’d do best getting exercise in the privacy of my own fenced in yard. I’m looking for a quiet home with no kids, dogs, or cats with a patient human who will love me as unconditionally as I love them. I am a little nervous because of my past. I can be shy at first but I warm up so quick once I learn you’re my friend, especially when you have treats! 

My nice foster tells me stories about the good life. About how there are other nice humans who always come back when they leave you. They give you meals and pets and treats. I dream about my forever human every night and I can’t wait to meet them. My foster tells me Rochester gets really cold.. something about snow? I don’t know what that is but I think it sounds perfect for staying in and watching Netflix.  

If your interested in meeting Winnie fill out an application!

www.operationfreedomride.com/dog

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email US at hollyliu93@gmail.com.
You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.
Dog's Name: Cowboy
Estimated Breed : Cattle Dog Mix
Approximate Age: 5 years
Approximate Weight: approx. 49 lbs
Currently Living at: Boarding
Adoption Fee: $375
DOG'S DESCRIPTION
Cowboy is a good boy once he gets to know you but is wary of new people. He is looking for a breed-experienced home who has the patience to earn his trust and love. Cowboy requires some leash work and would do better as an only dog in a home with no children.
Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Please "like" our Facebook Page for the most current events and new dogs.
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
Tucker is a Chihuahua/Dachshund mix, and he is about 1.5 years old and weighs 12 lbs.  Tucker loves life!  He is a friendly little guy, and he loves everyone he meets.  Tucker also loves his daily walks, and looks forward to meeting other dogs along the way.  Tucker has a very "enthusiastic" way of playing, so he may annoy older, less playful dogs.  Tucker cannot go to a home with cats because he just can't resist chasing them.  He should be ok with kids over the age of 7, and preferably ones who have experience living with dogs.
Tucker is protective of his food, so he needs to be fed separately from other dogs.  He sleeps through the night in his crate, but he will howl when left alone in a crate during the day, so no apartment life for Tucker.
He really needs a home where his people are with him most of the time.  Tucker has been dealing with some medical issues that have improved a lot and seem to be under control at this time.  Our adoption counselors and medical coordinator will be glad to discuss with you in more detail.  Please submit your application to adopt adorable Tucker at www.humanetomorrow.org.

Hi! My name is Barney, and I'm a new addition to Pawmetto Lifeline. My adoption fee of $450 includes my neuter surgery, deworming, microchip, and up-to-date vaccinations. 

I am a sweet guy who would feel most comfortable in a home without children or small animals. I need a home with cattle dog or working breed experience who knows exactly what to expect with a breed of a dog as smart as I am! 

My adoption is considered "Best Match". This means that I am looking for a specific type of home or certain qualities in my new family. I am not first come-first serve for any approved applicant. Pawmetto Lifeline's adoption advocates and my case managers would love to review your application to see if we are a good fit. animal.description:
Nala Came back to us January of this year. Unfortunately she had as a few altercations with the owners other dog. They loved her very much and didn't want to give her up but due to the fear of her being aggressive when it came to her food they felt it was best because they had younger children in the home. Nala came to use very very nervous afraid of us and showed some aggression to protect herself from her new surroundings. It didn't take long for nala to gain trust in a few female staff. We have been working very hard to get her comfortable around new people and slowly she is showing just that?. She has been able to be around Ruben which took her a little bit of time when she first arrived. But now she has gone up to staff without hesitation! Even our clinic staff have noticed the change in her which I awesome. Nala loves to go in water, loves walks and does good on leash, she does tend to pull a bit and like to run as well. But I think nala with the right person would be able to go up for adoption. Would definitely suggest a single female (could possibly be male), no younger kids or other dogs. But someone who is willing to come in a few times and work with her before making a finally decision or until we feel as staff she is ready to go to her new home. 
In Nala's recent move to our building three she has changed in behavior so well. She no longer is aggressively territorial through her doors or gates. She shows excitement and playfulness when we enter her room. She has become more playful with her toys. Before she had her dental surgery she was very head shy didn't like pets on her face probably due to pain in her mouth, but after her dental she has been better with touches on her head and face. She is thriving so well with strangers she was also was a part of the Fresno State research team. Nala has come out of her shell and loves to be cuddled and loved on. She would do so well with someone who has a lot of time to give her affection and the exercise she needs. 

If you think we might be a match, please visit please visit valleyanimal.org/adopt-info/ to download a Pre-Adoption Application and email dogs@valleyanimal.org to tell them that you want to meet me!

 Primary Color: Tan Age: 4yrs 11mths 3wks Animal has been Spayed

animal.description:

Emma came to Save A Pet as a stray with 3 sweet nursing puppies. A good samaritan actually witnessed Emma and pups being tossed from a vehicle onto the side of the road and immediately stepped in to save them... (how could anyone be so cruel??!) 
After Emma's puppies were weaned and went to a wonderful foster home, they all got adopted! However, Emma still waits for her forever home. Emma is so deserving of love and a happy ever after!

Emma is one of the most affectionate dogs at Save A Pet and we really want her to find the perfect home!

Update: Emma left the shelter for a trial-adoption and it was discovered that she does not like cats! (The lovely family who wanted so badly to have it work out has informed us that she is not good with cats and probably would be best as the only dog in the home as she wants all of the love for herself! )

Jake walks well on a leash, is housetrained, and is working on his basic commands.  This sweet boy can't wait to finally settle in his new home.


Thank you so much for your interest in adopting a dog from A New Chance Animal Rescue (https://anewchancear.org). We are a 501c3, tax deductible organization. ANCAR is a foster-based rescue, and we adopt within a 90 mile radius of Bedford Hills, NY.  You will find the adoption application here: (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-application/).  All fields on the application must be completed.
Please read about the adoption process (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-process/) so you'll know what to expect when you submit.   

Our dogs are in foster care and we do NOT have a shelter or boarding facility. AN APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED IN FULL AND APPROVED BEFORE A DOG CAN BE MET. This is a firm policy. Our busy volunteers are not able to respond to questions about the dog or dog meeting requests in the absence of an application.  We know these dogs very well because they are in foster care. Please read the profiles of the dog(s) you are interested in prior to submitting an application.  If there are specific requirements stated (ie: Fenced Yard or Canine Friend Required) these are included because they are vital to the happiness, health, safety and adoption success of that dog. 

We are only able to save as many dogs as we have foster homes (https://anewchancear.org/foster/faqs/) and resources for. We provide medical care including vaccinations, testing, deworming, spaying/neutering and microchipping before transporting our dogs. We provide all supplies, preventatives and any follow up vet care necessary while they are in foster care. These costs are high and the number of lives we can save is entirely dependent upon donations from people like you.  We do not receive funding from private foundations or government sources. If you can find room in your heart to help us, with any amount, we are truly grateful (https://anewchancear.org/help/donate/). We are a 501c3 organization, so all donations are tax-deductible. It is only through the kindness of supporters like you that we are 'changing lives...one tail at a time' by providing our dogs with 'A New Chance.' (https://anewchancear.org) 

Thanks so much.

animal.description:
Vega is a 42 pound, 3-year-old female with smiles and charm that makes jaded dog handlers break out in giggles. She is smart, eager, loving, and most of all adorable. She will sit pretty and balance herself by putting a paw on you. Its her compromise because she really wants to love on you, but she is trying not to jump. Did we mention that she is adorable?

She loves every person she meets. She has been winning hearts with her big, starry eyes and her derpy grin. She gets along with the fosters resident dogs. She prefers to play with the female, and Vega has been mostly neutral to the male. When yard-dog antics get out of hand, a simple Knock it off, is enough to remind her whos the sheriff in town.

Found as a stray in Oklahoma, Vega was still with milk, but no pups were around. Her ears are a little fly-bitten, but that doesnt take away a bit from her gorgeous expression or classic athletic build. When she entered rescue, she was nave to most of the wonderful things a Malinois should know.

It looks like for Vega, puppy training meant taking care of a few litters. She has a lot to learn, and she is an eager student. She loves attention, and training is a joy. She has picked up house-training, her new name, sit, settling in a large kennel, and she is learning to have manners with the people and other dogs in the house. She can show her hackles, but she redirects easily and improving with exposure.

Of all her classes, her favorite elective is TOYS. She didnt know what to do with them at first, but now she will take the hard chew toys out of the basket and scatter them around the yard to sample. Her foster laughs describing how Vega takes the jolly ball with a rope and plays fetch with herself. She has been very good and has not tried to eat anything that belongs to the humans.

The world has been turned upside down for Vega, and she is taking it really well. She is curious and shows a stable temperament so far. A falling chair made a loud noise next to her, and she just sniffed it and went back to her own business. She is adapting to the house rules, and she is beginning to get some supervised free time inside. She likes dog beds a lot, and she loves being close to the humans.

Vega can get anxious at times, but that is getting better as she settles into her new home. She is almost finished with heartworm treatment and has tolerated it well. She plays with the other dogs at the foster home, and she enjoys walks and training. However, cats are a definite no-go, and small dogs probably arent a good idea, either.

There were a few instances early on when she jumped a 5-foot fence to get to the front of the house, but she never left the property. Since she learned that her foster home has loving people and OMG! TOYS! she has not tried to jump the fence again. In fact, she shows all signs of becoming a Velcro dog. For a person who loves a dog who sticks close, Vega is a dream come true.

Training Vega will be a lot of fun. She wants to learn, and she has a very soft temperament. Her foster is impressed with Vegas intelligence, and is touched by her sweet nature. Basic obedience, hiking, a playing fetch, or maybe sports would be a good fit for Vega. If you want a sweet, friendly dog with a great smile to take on adventures, this good girl might be the fit. And did we mention that she is adorable?

If you have questions about this dog, please contact her adoption counselor, Teresa@madrescueinc.org.

If you are interested in adopting this pet, please complete an application at this link https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/24689/generic . 

We are an official 501C3 organziation that does not have a physical location. Our home address is in Michigan, however, the majority of our dogs are not located in Michigan. The physical location of each our our dogs is posted with the name of the pet or in the title area. If you are within 4 hours of the pet, please be prepared to pick the pet up. We do provide transport assistance, however, the applicant must drive 50% of the total distance of the transport. 

The information that we have available is in our posting. If you would like to discuss this animal additionally please fill out this application. Applications that are completed in our process and being considered as a match will speak to the foster home to gain more information about our adoptable dog. 

If you have questions about this pet please contact us at info@MADrescueinc.org. 

You may also call our toll free number at 844-MAD-RESQ or 844-623-7377. 

Additional information about all of our dogs for adoption can be located at our website MAD Rescue Inc

animal.description:
Roxy was adopted as a pup from our local shelter in 2016 and the adopter never got her back for her spay.  Fast forward to June of this year, and we got the call about her and two other dogs ( we are unsure if they were her pups or what) chained outside, and being subject to pellet guns and who knows what else.  We rescued all three and have been working with Roxy and her socialization.
She is learning to walk on a leash and doing well.  Slow introductions to other dogs and she is okay but she would love to be able to be the only dog so she can be the center of a family's world, not living outside tied up where she can be the center of abuse.
If Roxy might be the girl to add to your family, please follow our procedures below.

1. on line application
2. vet and reference check
3. phone call
4. home visit
5 meet and greet
6. adoption
We will travel up to two hours to do home checks. We also truly feel the dogs in our rescue have been through enough. We take in those who are injured, abused, neglected, sick, and abandoned. That being said we search for a home that they are never put in that position again and that fits their personality and needs the best. No more hurt or fear.

Storm has overcome some tough times in life, but when a wonderful woman and her beautiful family stepped in, the clouds seemed to disappear. No more looking from the outside in. For the first time in a very long time Storm has literally come in from the rain and the elements. Storm is now enjoying the freedom of running and walking without constraints.

It's amazing what love can do. Those once hopeless but hopeful eyes now shine brightly.  And Storm? Well she feels as blessed for the family who saved her as they do with her presence.

Storm would do well with children over 6 and would thrive with another sweet dog. Storm had been alone day in and out for so long that we feel she would thrive with another canine buddy to hang with. We promise it won't take away from the never ending love that Stormy has to give. Gray skies are sure to clear up when you adopt Storm and we promise that YOU will definitely put on a happy face.

animal.description:
Hey I’m Cooper! 
I am a sweet and very much affectionate young husky pup around 2-3 year old. My great rescuer Alljoy4paws literally saved me the last possible minute before euthanasia! I was very kenneled stressed and nervous in the shelter so they were scared of me but I was more scared of them! I had a feeling I wasn't safe although they took me out to the yard and I played nicely and had fun with a ball. I'm a good boy and nobody likes being locked up. I gave my rescuer so many kisses, if only the shelter could see me now when I feel safe. I’m better off to be the only dog, as I am more tolerant with other dogs, and didn’t really have the opportunity to play with them in my puppyhood, so I’m still learning and better my social skill and play style.  just really want a happy home, either foster or adoptive, who can give me the needed feeling of being and feeling safe, and happy, preferably no young kids, for some of them do not know how to respect me. I want to have someone to love, take me on walks and cuddle me so I know I'm loved. I am a very sweet soul, have been through a lot . I have made huge strides in the last couple months, and I need a husky savvy family, who has patience and understands what I need to get me to the optimum level, since I’m not perfect yet! I’m sort of weary of strangers and want to take time to warm up to them, but once I get to know you, you’re my best friend! 
I’m ready to go, neutered, microchipped and current on vaccines. 
Please contact Alljoy4paws about me, just email them: alljoy4paws@yahoo.com

Please, no phone calls. They will not be answered. Emails only.

If you have applied to adopt another dog from our organization and you are interested in this dog, please email to let us know you have an application on file. If you do not have one on file, please fill one out here:

https://homeboundhoundz.com/application-form

This is Asena. She is a stray from turkey. She is around 2 and a half years old. Asena is a confident, outgoing and friendly girl. We haven't been able to test her with kids but it is suspected that she'd do well. She has been around other dogs for quite some time and she does very well with others. She is an alpha female, so would likely do best in a home with a submissive dog or as the only dog. She loves to play fetch. She has a great temperament.

Our adoption fee is currently double the amount it normally is (during non-pandemic times), and for good reason. Because we do not have any flight volunteers (people flying from Turkey to Canada and offering to bring our dogs with), we are having to fly people from Canada to Turkey to get the dogs. We have to pay for each person's flight to Turkey and back, as well as roughly $600 per dog to fly. This totals at about $4000 per flight. The adoption fee currently is $900 CAD. It will go back down next year when things go back to normal and we have flight volunteers.

Hello everyone! My name is Samantha! I am a chunky sweet beagle girl! I am 6 years old! I have lost my owner and all of us are so devastated! We are hoping there is a family out there who can love us even though we aren’t puppies! I am fully house trained and crate trained and friendly with all other animals.

The adoption donation fee is $250 which is tax-deductible and goes towards the care of homeless pets with Pals for Paws. 

To expedite the adoption process you can fill out an application online at www.palsforpawsinc.com/adopt. Please note the adoption application doesn’t bind you to anything. Pals for Paws reserves the right to refuse any adoption application for any reason and at any point in the adoption process. 

To view our other wonderful Homeless Pets visit www.palsforpawsinc.com/pet-list ALSO be sure to LIKE Pals for Paws on Facebook at www.facebook.com/palsforpaws.inc 

All Pals for Paws Rescue animals are fully vetted:
*Spayed/Neutered
*Groomed
*Shots updated plus Leptospirosis 
*Micro-chipped
*Dewormed 
*On Heart-worm prevention
*On Flea and Tick Prevention
* Dentals are done if needed  

You only need to see your vet for a “meet n greet” of your new family member and to turn in their medical records.
 
Pals for Paws is a 501(c)3 animal rescue. Every penny donated and every penny received through adoption fees goes right back into the organization. There are times when the volunteers have to dip into their pockets to help the animals. We do not euthanize because a pet is sick, heart-worm positive, or has a broken leg; we fix it all, big and small. We strive to go above and beyond when caring for and socializing our animals. We understand the importance of getting to know each and every animal available for adoption in an effort to place them in the most perfect home possible. 
If you are looking for a particular type of dog or have special needs, We can help! Contact us at www.palsforpawsinc.com

He's highly motivated by food and we are learning we must wait our turn and "sit when treats are handed out! He loves his food!!! Due to his history, he is learning all the things most dogs learn as pups. He has been working on leash training and just went on his first road trip and was the perfect companion.

HW positive going through treatment 
Easy going

animal.description:
**We are only looking to place LUNA in a home with an existing prosocial pup**

LUNA is 11 months old and has had a little bit of drama in her short life! Her original family were unable to keep her (they had her from birth), and surrendered her to an organization. She was just arriving at a foster home when she slipped her collar and ran off onto the streets. For four days she was running around frantically and was finally caught. 

We arranged to take her as a transfer from the other group and now we're trying to find a home for this funny, silly, lovable JRT mix who will need an experienced home, and one willing to do some training with this little gal.

LUNA has some great qualities - she adores the people she is with, bonds very quickly to those she trusts, and is terrific with other dogs. She is house trained, and is super easy in many ways. She is playful, loves toys, loves to snuggle and be close. She enjoys car rides and nothing excites her more than a hike on a trail or a beach to romp on. She is a high energy young dog so needs an active home, preferably as a second dog.

But, LUNA has a high level of 'stranger danger' when she sees strangers - on the streets, on the trails or approaching a vehicle she is in. She is genuinely afraid of strangers and can growl, bark, even run up to strangers barking (which can scare folks!), and like many other dogs, is worse with her reactivity when she is on leash. 

This may be a result of not having been well socialised enough with a wide range of people when she was a young pup, or it could just be who she is - but we also feel that this is a behavior which will diminish over time with constant reinforcement that strangers can be the bearer of good things! We know this dog has a heart of gold, but she does have some anxieties that need work.

If you are experienced, and have another dog or dogs who would love a playful fun companion, and are looking for a small but active energetic dog, she might be right for you! We do not recommend children because of her current fear of strangers...

animal.description: Some of you might remember Sawyer, an eight-year-old, 39-pound German Shepherd mix.  He originally came to Home Fur Good in early October.  Sawyer is a bit of a conundrum.  He started out being turned in as a stray to the county shelter.  He was very briefly adopted out twice before being returned and then arriving at HFG.  Sawyer has been in a home with a family for a little over a month.  He has come back with mixed reviews.  His adoptive mom said he was the best dog she ever had.  Yet, Sawyer showed signs of aggression towards strangers who came into the home.  HFG had a dog behaviorist assess Sawyer, and it appears that Sawyer will protect his home and people.  He needs a home with dog experience and experience in training dogs through unwanted behaviors.  Sawyer’s most recent home had teenage children and he was exposed to friends popping in and out.  It's important to note that Sawyer is not fond of men. In fact, he would do best with a home that has zero men.  Zero men that will live with him and zero men that will visit, or a home that can safely separate Sawyer from male visitors.  Sawyer’s ideal home will be one that has a slower pace and less company for him to have to meet.  HFG’s dog behaviorist, from Couth Canine, is willing to work with the person or persons looking to adopt Sawyer. George is willing to consult with them and help set Sawyer up to succeed.  Sawyer knows sit, down, and possibly more; he is just keeping his tricks a secret.  His eyes light up when a ball bounces by, and he is very playful.  Sawyer is a collector of squeaky stuffy toys.  He is more of a hoarder than a rip ‘em apart kind of guy.  The more toys in his pile, the happier he is. The adoption fee is $150 and includes spaying/neutering, age-appropriate vaccinations, microchipping, and a free wellness visit at Phoenix Mountain Animal Hospital. Our adoption hours are Thursday-Saturday from 11:00 am-4:00 pm by appointment only.

This is actually 2 different litters of puppies that were dumped together in a ditch.  They were surrended to us at just four weeks old.  They were in terrible shape and fighting several infections.  It took lots of bottles, love and TLC but now at about 3 months old, these guys recieved a clean bill of health from our vet this week and they are finally ready to start looking for their forever homes! This combo litter is made up of 3 Catahoulas (one female, two males) and 5 Border Collies (three males and 2 females).  The Catahoulas may be a week older than the Border Collies.

Our adoption process for puppies in a litter is a little different than you may have experienced in the past.  We have found it works best if adopters apply for the litter, not the individual puppies.  Once the application is approved, we will reach out and set up meet and greets and invite the adopters to come and meet the entire litter.  This way, the adopters can choose a puppy based on their interaction with the puppies, not just a picture.  It also allows the puppies to have a say in who will be their forever family.  Sometimes a family may have a particular puppy in mind, but when they come for a meet and greet, the connection isn't as strong with the puppy they thought would be "the one" and they are able to choose the puppy they click the best with.  Puppies may or may not go home with their forever family the same day of the meet and greet.  It depends on the number of approved applications and the interactions between the puppies and the adopters. The decision is at the discretion of the Board Members present at the meet and greet.

The adoption fee for these puppies is $350. This includes all vaccines (4 Distemper/Parvo, 2 Lepto, a Rabies, and a Bordetella), appropriate dewormings, microchipping and the spay/neuter surgery.

We will be accepting applications until Oct 23, 2020.  Once the application window closes, we will take the next few days to process all the applications we receive and will then be in touch to set up meet and greets with approved adopters.  We hope to have this done by October 26, 2020 however, the amount of applications we receive determines how long it takes us to process them all.  We will contact you by the email address you entered on the application, so please make sure it is correct.  If you have not heard from us by October 29, 2020, please reach out to us by email.
Hootie's Haven takes the responsibility of choosing forever homes for our dogs very seriously and always has the best interest of our dogs in mind.  We reserve the right to deny an application for any reason and are not obligated to provide a reason. While this may seem unfair, we would hate to give someone hints about how to lie on an application for another rescue so that they were approved.  For example, if someone stated that they had 47 dogs seized by animal control in the past, and we told them that was the reason they were denied, they would know to leave that off the application the next time.  Most denials are not  for such extreme reasons, but our board has decided to put this policy in place for this reason.

We also post updates on our Facebook page, so please make sure you have liked our page and are following it so that you will see the updates.  You can also go to our page to see other pictures or videos of our dogs.  https://www.facebook.com/hootieshaven

Link to application

https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/22197/generic

animal.description:
Hi, I’m Finley! I’m a nine to 10 year old shy poodle mix with a great big heart looking for love.  I’ve come a long way since being rescued from the shelter and before that mostly knowing a life of neglect. Being in a foster home has taught me the ropes of life, what it’s like to get love on the daily with lots of hugs, cozy beds, and yummy meals... snack time is a definite perk!  I’ve learned a lot about home-life too and trusting people by watching the other dogs in my foster home. My perfect forever home will also have at least one other dog who I can follow and learn from, and hopefully become a best buddy. I don’t always pick up on things right away, but I do start to get it after repetition. My biggest hurdle right now is becoming 100 percent potty trained. I still have occasional accidents, but I’m sure I’ll catch on with time. Ideally, I’ll be in a home with easy access to a fenced yard and few or no stairs. I absolutely love exploring in the backyard and sunbathing, so a grassy area is a definite must! Overall, I’m in pretty good health... I was recently at the vet and had x-rays showing I have a good heart, blood work to confirm there’s no health issues, as well as urine analysis and a dental. I do, however, have dry eye and will need daily eye drops.  I get around okay, but am farsighted so seeing things super close can be confusing... for instance, sometimes a small step seems like it might be a cliff to me. I walk great on a leash and enjoy going on leisurely walks, but I do need a pet-parent who is patient and understands I didn’t come from a home where I was cared for in the same way as other dogs and is willing to provide guidance and consistency to help me learn.  I’d describe myself as pretty relaxed and easygoing, and will do best in a peaceful, low-key home environment where I can thrive.  Being pet and held was initially foreign to me, but I’ve begun to like this type of attention and really enjoy sitting on laps and having some cuddle time.  Key takeaways for my perfect forever home include another dog to socialize with, easy access to a fenced grassy area with few or no stairs, and a pet parent who doesn’t mind giving me eye drops, is patient, and can provide guidance to help me live my best life. If this person is you, then I can’t wait to meet!! 

If you live in the Los Angeles Metropolitan area and would like to meet Finley, please complete our online Adoption Application and we will be in touch. **Please note we only adopt in Los Angeles County and you must be at least 25-years-old.**

Adoption Application: http://www.beoplesbuddies.org/#!adoption-application/c1g7e

Visit our website to learn more about our foster-to-adopt process: www.beoplesbuddies.org

Please no calls. If you have specific questions not already answered on our website, please email us at beoplesbuddies@gmail.com

animal.description:
Please read the entire description before contacting us.
We do not adopt out of state
We do not adopt to families with children under the age of 10 years old
You must live within 1.5 hours of Vallejo, CA
If the animal is posted they are available.
We cannot guarantee any of our available dogs are "hypoallergenic"
All the information we have about them is in their description.
If you are interested in adopting a dog from us please review our process and complete our application at www.gunterslegacy.org/adopt.

Romeo is an energetic, 15lb, a 2-year-old mutt with likely Frenchie and chihuahua ancestry (and based on his love of feet and talkativeness, maybe some corgi, too!). He is as adorable as he is exuberant. At 15 pounds Romeo is able to indulge his charming cuddly streak on a lap but don't be fooled as he is a very athletic young dog and does best when well-exercised - he can easily complete a hilly five-mile hike in the morning, a 45-minute neighborhood walk in the evening, and still be ready for training and treats in the backyard at night. Romeo is a high-investment, high-reward adoptee with a lot of love to give who needs an owner committed to helping him mature his strong, charming little personality into a courteous and reliable family member. Romeo is a curious and fast learner who has responded well to obedience training during his five weeks in foster (as of Dec 7, 2020). Prospective parents should know and be prepared to help Romeo with food- and toy-related resource guarding behaviors that can and have escalated to lunging and biting (band-aids only, but a serious issue that needs attention). For this reason in particular Romeo would do best in a home without other little ones to "compete" with. He is housebroken, and while interested in other dogs is not reactive to other dogs, on or off-leash. 

Obedience: 
- Come/sit/stay (consistent indoors, inconsistent in distracting environments)
- Speak/hush (consistent on speak, working on hush)
- Loose leash walking (consistent in known environments; "come on back" works well as a reminder to stop pulling, reset, and go slower)
- Leave it (training stymied by reactivity to closed hands with food nearby)
- Thank you (for picking up or taking away a valued item - steady progress over four weeks, with lunges diminishing to infrequent)
Temperament:
- Curious, busy, affectionate, bossy, hilarious, cuddly 
- Signature Move: Flopping on his back and gesturing wildly for tummy pets.
- People: Initially reactive to tall men, but then warms up to them.
- Dogs: Interested, but not reactive on or off-leash
- Body sensitivity: After initial trust-building, loves being petted and relaxes when being held. Working on shake for minor paw sensitivity.
Housetrained: Yes

animal.description:
Lil Bit and Half Pint are 2 darling sisters.  They lived 4 whole years in a shelter!  They came from a small shelter in rural Arkansas, where they lived since they were puppies together, simply because nobody comes to adopt in that small town. We brought these girls up north so they can finally have the life they deserve!  They may look larger in pictures, but these girls are only around 30-35 pounds.  
The girls would be best in a calm and patient home where they can learn to be a part of the family.  Lil Bit and Half Pint are so loving and gentle, 5 minutes with them and you will fall in love!

*We are closed to the public for viewing. Please email adoptions@pawstinleypark.org if you are interested in adopting.

If you are interested in meeting this pet, please visit our website to check on their current availability: http://www.pawstinleypark.org.. Adoptions are limited to 50 miles from the shelter. We do not ship animals. Adoption fees for dogs are $125-$275 based on age. While we do our best, we cannot make guarantees on breed, exact age and house training of our dogs. Peoples Animal Welfare Society (P.A.W.S.) of Tinley Park, IL is a no-kill non-profit 501(c) (3) organization.

animal.description:
Tahoe is as goofy and cute as he is big, and we just love him! This tall, dark, and very handsome fellow tips the scales at about 85 pounds.  But don't let his size concern you--he is sweet as pie!  Tahoe is happiest when he can lean on, play with, or receive treats from a person.  While he is an adult dog, he has not abandoned his youthful puppy curiosity.  Prior to rescue, Tahoe had limited experiences so he will need a patient and kind person able to provide basic obedience training.

He is a very tall dog so he may have some Dane in him too. Tahoe has made many friends with the dogs, staff, and volunteers at our shelter. He loves to go for walks well on a leash. He works hard to please you and will chase balls for you until the sun goes down. He's yet to realize that he's supposed to bring them back--something you both can work on. 

Here at NMAR, we don't just find good homes for our dogs, we find the the specific good home for each specific dog. While we work towards those matches, our dogs are safe and happy in foster homes, or in our home-like shelter, where they have the chance to learn some life skills and show us what they need to be happy and healthy.

REQUIREMENTS:  Tahoe needs a family or a close buddy who is patient and will give him lots of attention and activity. He is super smart and loves to learn, so he needs someone who will continue to work with him on basic and advanced commands (this guy would love to work through an agility course), will continue to give him some good playtime with other dogs, and who will celebrate his exuberance. Oh, and probably a king-sized bed would be good. 

Adoption fee is $195 and includes: spay/neuter, parvo/distemper series of shots, rabies, bordetella, heartworm preventative while here, worming, and microchip. 

If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting Tahoe, please visit our website and fill out an adoption application: www.northmeckanimalrescue.org

animal.description:
This dynamic duo, Buffy & Rocket, have become best friends in foster & are looking for their forever family together.  Both dogs are wonderful, sweet, loving & fun young pups.  Buffy is very timid at first, she takes longer to warms up & want to snuggle by following Rockets lead.  Rocket is very curious, confident, outgoing & is a real attention hog. Both are still pups about 9mo and 1yr old and 10lbs. 

They are active little pups; up early to go potty (trained with a dog door), they enjoy the freedom to go out to run, play with toys, wrestle & sun bathe.  So an outdoor yard, a doggy door & secured fencing is required.  They bark when they play or at scary sounds & whine when left alone.  They still act like babies; chewing on blankets & stealing your shoes.  

As young pups they will need a family focused on their needs, with time to give them a ton of attention, be committed to training, give them positive encouragement, patience & understanding to help them to feel like loved family members.


The first step of the process is you must submit an application in order to set up a meet and great or talk with the foster family. Once application is submitted the foster parents will contact you to chat more about the dog and make sure they're a good fit and can answer any further question. The application answers most of all of our questions and can best match you. If you do not get the dog you apply for we can use your same application for 90 days towards another dog in our care and simply forward your app to that fosters 
http://form.jotform.com/underdogca/dog-adoption-application

All dogs will be fully vetted (Spay/ Neutered, Micro chipped, DHPP and Rabies Vaccinated) and other possible vet care prior to adoption.

The adoption fee is $300 which is considered a non refundable donation

visit us at underdogca.com or follow us on FB and IG @underdogca
https://www.facebook.com/underdogCA

animal.description:
Jack is a sweet little Jack Russel Terrier who currently lives in a foster home with 4 other dogs. He gets along very well with them, albeit they are all so much bigger than him.

Jack enjoys his daily walks around the neighborhood and his many forays in the fenced in back yard.

Jack is hard of hearing and his eye sight is not very good, but he gets around just fine once he knows the territory. He would do well in a home with another small dog and older, considerate children.

Jack does not care to be picked up but will tolerate it once he establishes trust. With some TLC, he warms up nicely and really loves his humans. He loves sitting next to you on the couch.

He is housebroken and loves his little crate, his man cave, with warm beds and blankets.

Jack loves his meals and can be quite noisy if it is prepared too slow. He also likes to bark at his foster parents when he thinks he deserves a treat which is pretty much every time he comes back in the house.

Jack is a wonderful little fellow who would love to find his forever home.

animal.description:
Hi, I'm Pandy! I was originally adopted from this shelter when I was less than a year old. Now I am back again, a little greyer and a little wiser. I was returned because I needed a surgery my family couldn't afford, but they loved me so much they gave me back to the shelter so I could get well. You see, my bladder makes stones if I'm not on the correct diet and too many stones are bad for a dog's bladder. I'm all fixed up and on the proper diet now. I really loved all the members of my family. in fact, it's a toss up which I like more: my family or playing in water. I can't even begin to describe how much I love water. The hose, a pool, a sprinkler...bring them on! I can't believe there are dogs that don't love water games. They are really missing out! I am a happy dog when in the loving home of my family. I do love to go for walks but there are things outside that I'm not so sure of. Some of these things are other dogs on walks, bikes, moving cars, skateboards, etc. The nice folks at the shelter have been helping me with this and my personal doctor gave me a pill to take that makes me less anxious around these things so I can have more fun on my walks. You know that song "Girls just wanna have fun"? Well, that's me. My family is my everything. I will bark at strangers but then I let them pet me so I guess I'm a pushover. So, what do you have to do to adopt me? You have to keep me on my prescription food, take me to the vet for regular urine checks & keep giving my my anxiety pills. Also, you need to have owned a dog before so the shelter can make sure you are used to going to the vet, you need to keep me as your one and only pet and you can't live in an apartment, condo or townhome because a girl needs her space, especially if she is gonna play lots and lots of water games! Sound like a lot to take on? I'm totally worth it, I promise!

Please note - we always take our animals back if for some reason it doesn't work in your home so we only adopt to the following Illinois counties: Cook, DuPage, Kane, Kendall, Lake, McHenry, Will.

animal.description:
This is Brutus, he is one of several Feist pups looking for a home. He and his brothers (Sam and Charlie) were given up by his breeder because they are not cut out to be hunting dogs (the sister Lucy was given up earlier this year). Brutus is the shyest of the bunch. He is very sweet but will need a little time to come out of his shell. He would do well with another more confident dog in the home. He is smart and learns quickly. He would be fine for a home with children as long as they are gentle. If more than one of these littermates were adopted together, we do offer a discount on the adoption fee. Brutus is neutered, up to date with shots, negative for heartworms/on prevention and crate trained. For adoption, please submit an adoption application via our website at www.myhstc.org

Adoption fee is $85 which includes all vet work. If a littermate were adopted to the same home, second adoption fee would be reduced to $45.

We prescreen all applicants prior to a meeting; to be screened, please submit an adoption application to www.myhstc.org

We do allow out of state adoptions. However, we do not ship nor transport sight unseen pets for many reasons. We require travel in person adoptions.

**ADOPTION APPLICATION REQUIRED via our website Rarerescue.org**

ADOPTION FEES: Our Adoption Fees vary based on adoptability to help all of the animals in our organization. Please make sure to read the adoption fee below in the bio.

BREEDS: We are not breed experts. The breed(s) listed for each adoptable are best guesses or suggestions.

STEPS TO ADOPT:

Read the adoptable’s bio below, including their adoption fee

Read  ADOPTION PROCESS page under the "Adopt" section

Complete the  DOG ADOPTION APPLICATION (located on our website RARErescue.org)

*Applications will be attended to before general inquiries. We may or may not have time to respond to general inquiries if you have not submitted an application.

We understand that it is important to you to find the right fit for your family. We feel the same way! The application is important and necessary for this reason. 

All of our Adoptables are:

*spayed/neutered
*up to date on vaccines
*heartworm tested if six months or older (and kept on heartworm preventative and treated for heartworms if positive when entering our program)
*microchipped prior to adoption

BASIC INFORMATION:

Suggested Breed(s): Rat Terrier
Gender: Male/Neutered
Approx. Age or D.O.B: Approx 18 months
Approx. Weight: 13 lbs
Coat Type: Short
Good around most dogs: Yes, but has guarding behavior of food, toys and people
Good around most cats: Yes, loves playful cats!
Energy Level: Medium
Fence yard may be required: Not required if leashed

Any other specifics:  
Patrick is little snuggle nugget who has a special personality that most terrier people know well. He loves to be held and he sleeps under the covers in the bed. He also plays well with other dogs and cats. He especially loves his feline foster sister and they are hillarious when they wrestle!

However, he is a resource guarder. If you are unfamiliar with the term "resource guarding", it means that he guards and becomes reactive towards a person or animal when they encroach upon his space while he is eating, playing with his toy or sitting/lying on a person. Therefore, his person or family would benefit from having experience with resource guarding. There needs to be some acceptance on the part of his adopters of what works best for Patrick and willingness to work with him. 

Patrick doesn't chew anything but his toys. He normally does not have any accidents when he's given potty breaks every few hours during the day and he sleeps through the night. If he's alone for more than 3 to 4 hours at his foster home, he wears a "belly band" (or male dog diaper) just in case!

Will you be a Hero in Patrick's story?

Visit our website/Click on Adopt to APPLY today!  RARErescue.org

Adoption Fee: $185.00



Please REMEMBER, All of our Adoptables are:

*spayed/neutered
*up to date on vaccines
*heartworm tested if six months or older (and kept on heartworm preventative and treated for heartworms if positive when entering our program)
*microchipped prior to adoption



PLEASE NOTE: We are a non-profit organization without municipal or government funding. Veterinary/Medical expenses are constant for an animal rescue. Our adoption fees not only help to provide vetting and care for the animal being adopted, but they also help to cover heartworm treatments and other treatable ailments that many animals, that would otherwise be euthanized, need in order to be made available for adoption.



Please understand that adopting an animal is a LIFETIME COMMITMENT to that animal and there will be veterinary expenses throughout their life that can often cost several hundreds, if not thousands of dollars (without pet insurance), especially without annual checkups and preventative care.  As a potential family for this pet you are responsible for their safety and that includes keeping them on your property.

***If you are not in the middle Tennessee area, transport can potentially be arranged to approved homes, depending on distance and local adaptability. We normally do not allow adoptions outside of 1.5 hours driving distance.

Thank you for choosing to adopt, foster, or aid in the rescue efforts of RARE!

animal.description:
We are now ready to start accepting applications for our gorgeous girl Godiva 

Godiva is approximately 7 years old and weighs about 65 pounds.  We believe her to be a pit/pointer mix (best guess ).  She is spayed, up to date on all vaccines and just completed heartworm treatment.  She is housebroken and has perfect manners in the home.

Godiva is a good girl who  found herself in horrible condition when her owner couldn't or wouldn't care for her.  She had a horrible skin infection, a severe eye infection, she was heartworm positive and had several fractured teeth.  Lucky for her, her "owner" surrendered her to the shelter and then she entered our care.  ALL her medical needs were addressed and today she is a happy, healthy heartworm FREE beautiful girl.

Godiva is now looking for a family, not an "owner".

  Godiva would benefit from  a quiet, predictable home with not a lot of people coming and going.  Godiva likes quiet.  Godiva can be a little nervous around some men, but can warm up.  No children, as they make her nervous.  

Godiva is fun and silly.  She enjoys cuddling in soft comfy beds or couches, chewing her favorite bones and warming herself in the sun.  She needs a patient adopter who will make her feel safe, secure and loved.  She needs a little time to adjust and warm up, once she does, she will be the sweetest friend.   

She can get along with calm, submissive dogs, with proper and slow introductions.  No cats or small dogs.  Godiva would also require a fenced in yard to she can enjoy her sunbathing! 


Godiva is located in Spring Hill Pasco County.   Please message us here or email us at lovetotherescueinc@gmail.com if you are interested.


**Inquiries by email only please. We do not respond to phone call inquiries**
