animal.description:
Meet Ralphie! Our boy is not for the faint of heart. He is...well...a pistol! He is looking for a specific home and he intends to be, shall we say...picky.

Ralphie is a champion ball player. And he won't share his ball with just any ole person. He has to approve you. Once you're approved you've got the seal of approval for life. He bonds deeply with his human.

Ralphie was saved from Hurricane Harvey. He arrived in Delmarva as a part of a lifesaving transport out of the disaster zone.

Ralphie told us under no circumstances does he want to share his life with a kid. He owns all of the balls in the house ...and he's not sharing. His perfect parent is a pitching machine and must be up for a game of ball every night. He would prefer if you own a minimum of a dozen tennis balls because he'll play with 3-4 during one game.

Ralphie is quite the connoisseur. He'll appreciate it greatly if you know how to serve up the grub. He enjoys mealtime almost as much as his game of fetch.

Once you've passed Ralphie's inspection - he will lavish you with love. But know this - you'll have to earn it - and it will take time. 

He is crate trained and housebroken. He is vaccinated, neutered, heartworm negative, and microchipped. He hopes you are too.

Musts:

Ralphie must be adopted within one hour of the rescue. Multiple visits will be required. Adopter must have a fence. 

If you want to swipe right on this guy - visit our website for the adoption application. www.hillhounds.org

animal.description:
(Version française disponible ici: 
https://www.sitwithme.ca/fr/dogs/zevs/ ) 

Zevs
Male
6.5 years 
Rottweiler/ Mix


Dogs: Possibly, read below
Cats: No 
Kids: No, 15+ okay

Housing Type: Detached Country or Semi-Country home. Please do not apply if you live in a busy city. 

Fenced in Yard: Required. An exception can be made for a private country setting and in this case, no fence is required as long as he has supervised long line exercise and his person understands he cannot be off leash. 

Medical: Some food sensitivities. 

Special: Zevs will need to meet his new person a few times before moving to his new home. As such, applicants must be within 2 hours drive of Ottawa and must be willing to come to Perth a few times to meet him. Zevs is a RAD (Recovery Adoption Dog) due to his difficulty meeting and trusting new people. His trial into a new home will last up to a month and his placement includes 3 in-person or virtual training sessions with a professional trainer if needed. 

Zevs is a very sweet boy who does struggle when meeting new people. Slow introductions to people are best for him. Because of this, he requires a home that doesn't have a lot of people coming or going. With the people who he trusts, Zevs is a big sweetheart who is super affectionate and sweet. Due to his strong love for familiar people and home, Zevs has a tendency to take on the job of guarding. Careful attention to making roles and responsibilities clear will be essential. Zevs adopters will work with his trainer to learn his recipe for success. Zevs is a goofy guy who enjoys throwing his toys in the air, running around in circles and digging holes in the yard. When inside, Zevs is a cuddle bug and a couch potato who loves to Netflix and chill. 

Zevs is food motivated and this makes it easy to bond and work with him. He requires an experienced owner who will continue to provide him with structure and training to allow Zevs to grow and thrive. 

Zevs has successfully stayed with another dog previously and has been able to play and be with other dogs once he has been introduced properly to them. He can be rude and over the top, so tolerant dogs would be best along with people that are willing to teach him boundaries and how to play appropriately with others. 

You can apply at www.sitwithme.com/zevs

animal.description:
Lorelei is about a year old, 40 pound bull dog mix. Our Lorelei has had a roller coaster of the last few months. As part of a massive 11-dog transport from Georgia, she was the actual Momma to Baby Rory and the "acting Momma" to every other puppy on the transport. Despite having little to no milk left, every pup attempted to nurse from her and she patiently and dedicatedly let them. Lorelei was found to be heartworm positive. Upon being given her first routine dose of monthly medication for heartworm preventative, her body revolted. The dying microfilaria caused her to have seizures! It's a rare response... with the dedication and devotion of her foster and the commitment of our vets to figuring her out, we have now discovered Lorelei just needs a five day course of steroids coinciding with her monthly Med and she does perfectly fine taking them now! She's had skin issues we addressed, Urinary issues, vaginitis... it seemed at every turn was another hurdle for our girl.

In between all these medical marvels, Lorelei learned about the good life. She vacationed in the mountains with her foster family. She went to breweries and had weekend outings with her foster momma. She met lots of folks who instantly fell in love with her. She learned to play, to enjoy the freedom of a yard and the joy of a long walk. She learned to love by being loved.

It's time. Lorelei is ready for her forever home. She's doing wonderfully going through her heartworm treatment via the slow kill method with the steroid addition monthly. She has lived in a home with three small dogs and done phenomenally well. She's besties with the little chi-mix girl in her her foster home.

In her forever, Lorelei would like soemone to continue to broaden her horizons with experiences. She also needs a sweet, playful pup to be her friend.

Lorelei is spayed up to date on vaccines, and microchipped. Adoption donation is $250.

If you would like to meet any of our dogs please fill out an adoption application on www.maxxandme.org
Maxx & Me is an all volunteer, all foster home rescue and do not have a shelter. Please allow at least 48 hours for applications to be processed (missing information may slow the process, so please take your time and be thoughtful in your answers). All dogs posted are available (so no need to ask). We place dogs based on best home for each dog and not order of applications received. Email us at maxxandmerescue@gmail.com for updates and questions. Thank you for choosing rescue.

I was born with a spinal deformity and I am unable to know when I have to “go.” While here at the rescue, the community came together and raised funds for me to have a spinal surgery to see if it could be fixed, but it could not. I am incontinent for life.  Searching for a dedicated human that doesn’t mind diapering me when inside, which I tolerate well.  I even do a cute dance while being diapered.  My ideal life is to run outside most of the time and when inside, wearing my diaper.  I have a loving nature for my owners, but am fairly unsocialized so slow to warm up to strangers. animal.description:
Zora is the snuggliest, happiest, goofiest girl! Anyone who has met her can tell you, she has the brightest spirit in the world and will instantly steal your heart!

Zora:
- Loves people
- Loves dogs
- Loves playing outside 
- Loves treats and takes them so gently
- Has gotten along with some cats and has reacted toward others — She likely would just need a slow introduction

We pulled Zora from the county shelter in honor of National Dog Day. The volunteers there were in love with her and were desperate to get her out. 

When we picked Zora up, she couldn’t walk well, due to emaciation and weakness. She collapsed in the parking lot, had to be carried into the house, and had to be held up while eating. Now, our girl is so much stronger! She absolutely loves to play at the dog park and take naps with her human! If you're looking for a dog to make you laugh, play with, and then nap with, Zora is your girl! 

Zora has some special needs, so please read that portion of her profile, too. Zora will be spayed before being adopted out.

animal.description:
MEET GEORGE!!

This charming and engaging 8 year old, 38 lb beagle has been medically cleared and is ready for his forever home! George lost his sight, but you'd never know it! There are three things that make George ecstatically happy~ belly rubs, children, and toys. When you rub his side, he will flop over and expose his entire belly so you don't miss one single bit of it. When he hears the giggling of children, he will run to find that small person and woof for attention. When George comes across a toy, he will zoomy in a circle with his ear down to the ground so he doesn't lose track of where he is. He is extremely resourceful, and his other senses work very well.

George has been through a lot in his life, and we made a promise to him that we would find him the perfect family. That family will preferably have a one story house so he doesn't fall down stairs; a ton of patience to help guide him around in his new abode; a fenced in yard or other safe space to play with his ball; and an available hand for endless belly rubs; and dog savvy children. In his perfect home there are no other animals because he deserves to be the one and only and get all the attention.

George is house broken and crate trained and will come when he's called and knows 'sit.' He'd prefer to actually sit in your lap or lean into your legs, and we think that is pretty adorable. After all, a relaxed sit is still a sit in our book.

Are you the happily ever after for George?

George is up-to-date, neutered, and blind. His adoption fee is $300.

animal.description:
Hey there (I'm) Delilah. 

I had a rough start before I got to FRR, but now, after decompression time, professional training with the folks at Triangle K9, and proper introductions to other dogs, I am focused on my future. Are you part of it? I hope someone reading this is.

I am still a little insecure about meeting new people and may duck my head or avoid contact initially. If you will give me some space, I will come around and invite you to pet my wiggling body and wagging tail. 

I am a full grown, but still young, energetic pocket pit (35#). I am totally housebroken, settle nicely in a crate, and am learning basic house manners (apparently stealing dog treats off the counter is NOT ok) and how walk politely on a leash. 

I have lots of energy, am faster than a speeding tennis ball, can leap sectional sofas in a single bound (particularly if the words "walk, "outside , or "hungry are mentioned). A house with a yard is NOT needed, because I can jump about 3' from a standstill and clear a solid wood 6' fence from a trot if there's proper motivation on the other side (proper motivation = squirrel). So, I will need someone who doesn't plan to leave me in a yard and is up for a couple of good walks a day. I'm getting better with each walk about my lash manners and enjoy my neighborhood walks. I would probably love to get involved in some kind of dog sport, I'm little, fast, smart and love pleasing my person. 

I am also an expert cuddler that likes to curl up on the sofa at the end of the day or if you get up really early and want company while you drink your coffee and watch the news.
In my current foster, I have 2 BIG dog friends, 1 male, and 1 female. I was nervous about meeting them at first, but my foster took it slow and supervised our interactions, allowing me to go at my own pace until I understood dogs could be my friends. My foster recommends if you have a dog you do the same type of slow, monitored introductions. My foster is not sure I'd be good with cats, because I might confuse them with squirrels, especially if they run from me. 

If I sound like your kind of girl, fill out an application and arrange and they'll connect you with my foster!

animal.description:
Welcome to the Wonderful World of Rescue Dachshunds. Look around and read their bios. Find a few whose personality seems to fit well. Consider one of our Well Seasoned Seniors who are truly wonderful and have so much to offer. Need help finding the best fit? We'll help with that too. Please fill out an application and let's get you all matched up with a loving new "furever' companion and friend. You'll find the application on the "Available Dogs" page.

NOTE:

Adoptions to Central/South Texas residents only

Standard Adoption Fee Adult Dog: $250 ea. Puppy Adoption Fee: $300 ea. Reduced rates for Seniors dogs (10 and up). Reduced rates for pairs (when adopted together). All adoption fees are subject to sales tax per the State of Texas. DDRTX only adopts in Central/South Texas.

Email: ddrtxinfo@gmail.com Primary Website: www.DDRTX.org
Rex is a sweet, older gentleman. The vet guessed him to be about 12 years old and he came in very thin. We are working on getting some weight on him.

He takes a few days to get used to someone, but then once accepting them, has no problem coming and nudging you hand to pet him, and will keep nudging until he satisfied. He's very gentle and quiet, haven't heard him bark yet.

He's happiest curled up in a soft blanket or dog bed. He's learning the doggie door, but also alerts you when he needs to go out by standing by the door.

Still has a little spunk in him and will "dance" around wanting your attention. Perfect for someone who is home often and wants a companion.

Rex is ready for adoption. He will need to be on a kidney diet the rest of his life to keep his kidney healthy. If you have questions about that, just ask. It is an a prescription food you can get from your vet or maybe even Chewy.
Love dachshunds and not ready to adopt or circumstances won't permit having a dog? How about being a sponsor or making a donation. Every one of our dachshunds receives excellent medical care along with day to day food, love and housing. Being non-profit, we rely on generous individuals like yourselves to help save these fur babies. You can do this specifically for one dog with the sponsor button on their webpage or a general donation on our "How To Help" page. Easy and quick through Pay Pal or your debit/credit card. You generosity is sincerely appreciated by all and is tax deductable. Need other ideas? You'll find tons of them on the How to Help tab. All contributions are tax deductable.

Diamond Dachshund Rescue of Texas is a non-profit 501(c)(3) volunteer organization with focus on rescue and adoption of pure breed Dachshunds. All dogs are fully vetted and housed on private property. Meetings are scheduled upon adoption approval. Thank you for your continued support to the rescue and shelter communities!
Opt to Adopt!

animal.description: Kangaroo is ready to bounce right into your life! We think this beauty is possibly a Lab and Terrier mix and around 2 years old. Kangaroo is a sweet and friendly girl that has settled in quickly to her foster home. She came to Labs and More with her one pup and now she is ready to move on from motherhood in favor of a forever home to call her very own. She is currently being treated for a medical condition and won't be ready to meet any families until later on in the year. If you think you are ready to add to your family by adopting Kangaroo, then fill out an adoption application on our website today! If you have adopted from us before or are already approved with a coach, reach out to your coach for the next steps. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. Thank you for rescuing.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description:
This gorgeous gal is Shelby!

Shelby is a playful 3 year old pup and she loves to run round the backyard and play fetch! She also enjoys going on walks. She has great manners and does well only chewing on her toys, is potty trained, crate trained, and knows lots of commands! (sit, shake, down, roll over) Shelby loves to snuggle and hang out on the couch about as much as she likes being active. She's a great blend of energetic and cuddly!

Shelby does well with other dogs, but can be a bit overzealous in wanting to play with her kitty friends. She has lived in a foster home with older children and has done well with them. She can need some time warming up to new men, but give her a little time and space and she's a friend in no time!

Shelby is vaccinated, spayed, microchipped, heartworm negative and her adoption fee is $200. Need a snuggly, loving pup in your life? Shelby is ready to bring you all kinds of joy! Apply to adopt Shelby by completing an application on our website! http://mhrindy.org/adoption-inquiry/***Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.***

animal.description:
*Due to state laws regarding out of state adoptions, we cannot adopt to families in Massachusetts or Rhode Island.*

Glen Coco is a special needs dog looking for a rather specific type of family. Our ultiamate goal is to match him with a foerver family. Please read his description in full prior to inquiring about him.

He was rescued from a dire situation - he was kept on a chain attached to a tree with no food, water, or shelter. Of course, this had adverse effects on his behavior. When the owner of the property approached him to turn him into animal control, he bit her. He was sent to death row for aggression. I met Glen during a routine visit to see what dogs our animal control had in custody. I met and spent time with Glen and determined that he has too much good in him to be euthanized. He has been in my home with my family for about 4 weeks. He plays great with my dogs and doesn't bother my cats. He does have issues with food guarding and has to be fed in his own crate. He loves to get pets and cuddle on the couch. He is leash trained, crate trained, and doing well with house training. The only problem he has is with discipline. When he has an accident or is told to get off the couch, go to his crate, or go outside when he doesn't want to.. he nips. He doesn't attack, he doesn't break the skin. It's more of a warning bite than anything, but is something that will be an issue for his adoptive family. It isn't his fault that he reacts this way. He was abused and neglected and most likely never taught anything with compassion and understanding. He really is a sweet dog who deserves a second chance at life. 

Listed breed is an educated guess made by our veterinarian and is NOT a guarantee - this also means we have no way of knowing what a puppy's adult size will be.

This dog is currently being fostered in Mississippi and will be transported via Barton's Barkers transport services upon adoption. Their adoption fee is $450 and includes spay/neuter, age appropriate vaccinations, a nose to tail vet check, microchip and transport costs. Second Chances lists dogs as being available in White River Junction, VT because we transport our dogs to the area every 3rd week after they have been adopted. All of our local shelters have a high euthanasia rate due to overpopulation so we created our rescue group to primarily adopt to the northern states to help keep as many dogs as we can from entering our kill shelters.

animal.description:
Adoption fee: $175

Physical appearance: Hickson is estimated to be about 10 years old. He is black and tan and cropped and docked. At some point before arriving in rescue he was debarked, so when he tries to bark, it sounds more like a raspy cough.

Personality: Despite Hickon's age, he will run and play with the best of them. He is generally calm and well behaved, but he'll also have some spurts of energy and play with his foster sister. He needs to be watched when playing because sometimes his foster says he becomes "obsessed" with his foster sister and he needs to be separated to calm down. and not bug her to death. However, he also has some days where he totally ignores her. His preferred method of play is to start with a stalk, which then turns into pure goofiness.

Why hes in rescue: Hickson wandered up to the home of a good Samaritan who tried to find his home. After a wild goose chase, his owners were found through the microchip, and they said they did not want him anymore. The good Samaritan thought she found him a home who ended up dumping him in the shelter when they found out he had heartworms.

Manners and training: Hickson knows how to sit, laydown, and will come when called. he walks pretty well on a leash and when he does try to pull responds well to a correction. He does well with people, rides well in the car, and is okay in a crate. He is potty trained but is showing some minor signs of separation anxiety. He does well with other dogs but will not be adopted to a home with another male. he will need a slow introduction to any other dogs in the home and be monitored closely so he doesn't get too obnoxious and learns boundaries. We do not know how he is with cats. Since he is very clumsy when he plays, we do not recommend a home with smaller children as he will likely knock them over.

Vetting: All of our dogs are brought up to date on rabies, Bordetella, and combo, negative for intestinal parasites and heartworms, neutered and microchipped before adoption. Hickson tested positive for heartworms when arriving at rescue and is currently undergoing treatment. He will complete treatment before being adopted out.

animal.description:
We are currently closed to the public and will only be responding to pet inquiries accompanying an online adoption application. Once animals are posted, we immediately begin receiving applications. With one volunteer available to review all applications, we appreciate your patience as you wait for an email response. Adoption appointments are scheduled in the order that approved applications are received. You can find our adoption procedures and online application at warmhearts.org/adopt.

Princess was abandoned on our property, so we don't have any background information. It is always very sad to see a senior dog displaced from/by their family, because their odds aren't great that they'll be chosen for adoption. Princess is a laid back girl who--as you can guess--is quite confused by being here. She truly needs to get back into a home where she can live out her life in dignity. Princess's estimated DOB is 8/1/2013. She weighs about 76 pounds and could use trimming down some.

HSPC's adoption fee is seventy-five-dollars through December 31, 2020, unless stated otherwise within the pet's description. At times, our adoption fees are lowered during special events that are posted to our website or Facebook page. Every pet that is available for adoption has been spayed/neutered, microchipped, and is up-to-date on vaccinations including heartworm preventative (canines). Adopters are required to schedule a wellness exam with their veterinarian at their cost within 7 days of adoption.

Please only submit one application. Once you are contacted by email, you will have an opportunity to provide us with any additional animal(s) under consideration.

animal.description:
I came to rescue when I was a pup. I had been hit by a car and had a horrendously broken leg. A nice person sponsored my surgery and a nice foster home took me in so that I could recover. My leg healed and I was adopted. Sadly, the family could no longer keep me and I was returned through no fault of my own. I am back in rescue and ready for find my FOREVER family! I am such a good boy! I get along great with other dogs and I LOVE LOVE LOVE kids! I adore them! I've never met a stranger. I love everyone! I am the PERFECT family dog!!! However because of my size and energy, I need to be in a home with older children. I wouldn't want to be excited and accidently knock over a small child. I would feel so bad if I accidently hurt one. I am housebroken, and listen well to instructions. I really want to please. Due to my past injury, I favor one of my hind legs a little, but it doesn't slow me down a bit. I love to play, and I'm a great walking/hiking partner. I LOVE playing with other dogs and I'm super affectionate with people. I am so good natured! I'm happy and smiley all day! Fill out an adoption application to meet me! Learn more about me and fill out an online adoption application on the From the Heart Rescue website at: www.fthar.org.

My requested adoption donation includes my spay/neuter, age appropriate vaccinations and medical care to date, microchip implantation and registration, collar, leash, ID tag, health check-up and one month of free pet health insurance (some restrictions may apply).

If Im not exactly what you want, please visit my other friends in rescue at From The Heart Rescue on our website at www.fthar.org.

animal.description:
Meet Ryder.............a true survivor!  He's looking for a dedicated and qualified person who can walk through his healing process with him. 
 
Ryder is a handsome eight-year-old male Pointer/Pit mix who has endured some big-time neglect.  However, he also has proven to be on the road to a very happy/healthy recovery. He is such an awesome dog, and given everything he's been through any dog lover would want to get him out of the shelter ASAP.  Even the staff realize it’s just not the right environment for Ryder.

Ryder continues to recover physically.  He has demonstrated a few situational behavior issues when around strangers. As we advocate for his needs, we are looking for a very particular forever or foster home so he can prosper into new life adventures.

Ryder was found back in April literally boarded up with another dog inside an abandoned car.  He was absolutely emaciated and covered head to toe with infected sores and bite wounds from the other dog.  Even his poor eyes and the bottoms of his feet were infected.  The dogs had both been alone in the car, starving, for who knows how long.  Ryder was only about 39 pounds when he was found.  A month later, Ryder was up to a healthy 65 pounds.  He has been on various medications and treatments over the several months as a team of dedicated people try to get his skin, eyes and paws back to normal.  This guy has made HUGE progress and looks like a totally different dog. He's probably going to be recovering, on meds, and needing semi-regular check-ups for a while.  He last vet visit was in August. They started him on a new course of antibiotics, eye meds, and skin meds.  He has been growly with male veterinarians when he's first met them, although he was fine with them after just a few minutes.

Behaviorally, Ryder is your typical smart, super-goofball Pitbull.  He’s very intelligent and eager, lots of healthy energy for his age, good on-leash, totally housebroken, very affectionate and responsive with people he knows.  He has done well with most of the other dogs he's met.  Ryder is generally more comfortable with women.  He has been kennel-reactive to strangers walking by, both male and female.  Mostly just barking, but sometimes he will lunge at the gate if the stranger (with a backpack, hat and/or sunglasses) lingers.  Since he was a homeless person's dog for the majority of his life, his protectiveness is quite understandable.  His triggers will be important to respect as Ryder learns to increase his ability to trust. Potential!  Potential!  Potential!  He’s almost there!
In the right foster or forever home, Ryder is going to do amazingly well!   He’s such a great dog when he's in a comfortable setting.  Clearly, he has been through many difficult situations.  He has not given up!  

If interested, please send a brief description of what you can offer Ryder. ellen.second.chance@gmail.com

animal.description:
Please meet Derby boy! Derby is a 5-year-old, neutered male with a sweet gentle spirit and to meet him is to fall in love. He is playful and energetic as well as obedient and knows his basic commands. He likes walks and car rides and most of all playing and playing - then downtime with humans. Exercise is a very important part of Derby being successful in a home.

Derby needs to be the one and only dog in your life, but he will fill your heart with so much joy that he will be enough! He likes kids but would do better with older children (over the age of 12) as he appreciates their "playstyle". He doesn't quite understand younger children.

He needs a family that will continue with his training and understands that he will do better with some boundaries in place. He LOVES people and is eager to learn and please, and is a quick study. We continue to work on training for Derby and are working on crate training while he waits for his new family. A consultation with our trainer will be available for Derby's new family. Most of all, Derby wants nothing more than to find a family to love.

If you would like to meet Derby please complete the application at www.azpawsandclaws.com and we can arrange a meet and greet. Thank you for rescuing.'

animal.description:
Hi there, I’m Maya and I think I could be the girl of your dreams. 
 
I’m a sassy 66 lb. gorgeous, cashmere soft, 8-year-old English Bulldog and I’ve been deaf since birth – don't worry about communicating though, I’ll let you know when I want something.  My foster family has also worked with me to develop a series of signs and taps on my body that help us “talk” with each other and they seem to be working well and I’m improving every day.  In addition I have this amazing loving gaze and can communicate with my expressions and will put my full bear claw paw in your lap when I want you to pet me. 
 
I am at my happiest sitting in the backyard, strolling the neighborhood or going for a car ride.  I love walking – I’m slower than I used to be and have some arthritis in my back legs but that doesn’t stop me. Oh, and I do have to occasionally stop and have a roll around in the grass, a little nap or drink from one of those cool outdoor sprinklers.  I love to get my whole head in there and soak it up.  My foster family says it’s like a good face pressure wash for me.  I am also obsessed with car rides. I am happy to go anywhere you are willing to drive me and I am super well behaved in the car.  I either snooze away happily or gaze out the window at the great big world.  When my foster family dangles the car keys I make a dash for the backdoor.  
 
When I was rescued, I was really struggling with an undiagnosed illness but through amazing doctors and the good folks at CEBR we found out that I have Cushing's disease. I’m on medication for it which I’ll need to take for the rest of my life but the good news is that it’s doing its job and my Cushing's is under control. Check out my gorgeous fluffy white coat. My foster family and my doctors are still trying to figure out one last thing that I’m dealing with but we think we are going to figure it out soon.  Because of this I’m still currently wearing a diaper most of the day but stay tuned for exciting updates. 
 
I love treats – I can be a little snappy as I’m very eager to eat them but I’ve been working with my foster family on taking them gently and am making real progress. I am also not keen on having my face cleaned and am sensitive about my overall bulldog grooming routine but I am becoming more open as I learn that the good treats get offered when I allow this to happen (I am very food motivated). As a bonus, I do love having my tail pocket cleaned.  
 
When I became ill, I started to have separation anxiety probably because I was just feeling so icky all of the time and needed humans near to make me feel safe.  As I’ve gotten better my foster family has been working with me on this but I would find it comforting to live in a home where people might be around more.  If you’re asking, I’d also like to have a home with fewer stairs as I struggle a little going up and down, especially when I’m tired. To be clear, I can do stairs pretty darn well but I make my Foster Dad carry me upstairs at bedtime – he's a sucker! 
 
Are you my forever family?  Please send me a note. I’d love to meet you.  
 
Love Maya 

If you would like to donate to Maya's care, please go to our website at http://shopcebr.com/products/donation.


HOW TO QUALIFY FOR A CEBR BULLY To determine if you qualify to adopt one of our adorable bullies start by viewing our Adoption Area Map. If you fall within the boundaries and are interested in our bullies the first step is to complete an application by visiting www.ebullymatch.com

animal.description:
Asha is a true survivor in every way. She was born in a filthy and horrible Pennsylvania puppy mill. When she did not qualify medically for a health certificate to be sold because of a severe heart murmur at just 8 weeks old, the puppy mill operator held on to her for another couple of months to see if she would grow out of it and considered using her for breeding purposes. He ultimately decided to release her to Finding Shelter and she was diagnosed with a serious heart condition called sub aortic stenosis. Asha’s litter was severely under socialized but with the help of her foster family, she has made progress meeting strangers. Asha needs a very special and experienced home who can handle her progressing heart condition (she takes daily medications and will need them for the remainder of her life) and be patient with her as she is nervous meeting new people. Asha loves toys, she loves to cuddle on the couch and would like to be high energy but her activity needs to be controlled because of her heart. She would do well as an only dog so she wouldn’t try to engage in high activity play. Asha is a wonderful girl with so much love to give and is extremely smart. She just needs to find her perfect match!

*All dogs will go through a transition period after finding a new home and may need a “refresher course” in house-breaking.

animal.description:
Meet Thor!
Thor is a 6 year old German Shepherd rescued from the shelter in June, and quickly won the hearts of his foster family! When he was rescued, it was clear that he had some issues with his hind legs. After consultations with a vet, neurology specialist, orthopedic surgeon, it was determined that he did not need surgery, but that he would benefit from physical therapy. He has already had a couple of sessions and the exercises seem to be helping his back legs get stronger. His foster family reports that his demeanor has changed significantly since they first received him. When he first arrived, he was not feeling his best – he had an upset stomach, and he was on crate rest due to his leg injuries. Now with some pain management, and alot of TLC, his personality is shining! He is affectionate, loyal, playful, and very smart. Every morning he loves to get spoiled with a full rub down. He is quite food motivated, which has made training very easy! He loves to play fetch, and will often bring you a toy to ask you to play. He loves going on walks (not too long, as his legs will tire), but perhaps his favorite thing to do is go on car rides! He has a very funny quirk where he spins and spins in circles, especially when he is excited. He sleeps in his crate and he is fully potty trained.

Because of Thor’s hind legs, he will need to be placed in a home where there is carpet or non-slick surfaces, as it is difficult for him to walk on hardwood floors without slipping and potentially injuring himself. He also is not able to climb stairs (a few steps he can handle, and he has no problem jumping in the car!). We would like to place Thor in an experienced adult home or one without small children. 

Apply at angelsfurryfriends.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
Please meet Boswer! He is a 15-month-old, 64-pound, neutered Boxer, who is likely part bulldog. Bowser is very sweet and has a LOT of energy. He is quite strong and will need an owner who has Boxer or bully breed experience. Bowser has spent the last couple of months with one of our trainers and has done quite well. It will be important that his new human(s) continue working with him so that he can become the best version of himself possible. Training should be pretty easy as Bowser is very food motivated. 

Speaking of food, it seems Bowser was without food for some time as he's very uncomfortable with anyone near him while he's eating from a bowl. His trainer has made great strides at improving his trust, but this is a work in progress and his new home will need to follow the protocol to help him continue that progress. Please note that he’s totally fine when taking treats or having treats tossed to him.

Bowser likes to play with toys and is perfectly happy entertaining himself while his people are busy doing other things around the home. He also enjoys a nice game of tug, but be ready…this boy is strong! Bowser also plays very rough and has not been able to learn how to appropriately play respectfully with other dogs, so he will need to be the only dog in his forever home. And due to his strength and rough play, his ideal home will be one without any kids around; and also, no cats for Bowser.

Bowser was found as a stray, so we don’t know anything about his background, but it seems clear he’s not had a lot of interaction or exposure to the outside world. His family will need to introduce him to new things and experiences slowly and be very patient with him so that he can gain confidence and learn to trust.

Bowser is going to make a great “hang around” kind of dog. When he’s calm, he’s very sweet and will enjoy simply being with his people. We are confident that with patience, and clear and consistent guidance, Bowser is going to blossom into a wonderful pup. If you are interested in welcoming this handsome guy into your heart and home, please let us know by submitting an adoption application - https://www.mustluvboxersrescue.com/adopt.

We do provide transport assistance, however, the applicant must drive 50% of the total distance of the transport. 

The information that we have available is in our posting. If you would like to discuss this animal additionally please fill out this application. Applications that are completed in our process and being considered as a match will speak to the foster home to gain more information about our adoptable dog.

animal.description:
Hi my name is Shamu, but they lovingly refer to me as Moo Moo! My heart is huge and I love everyone I meet! I will do great with a loving family who has time to play with me in a fenced in backyard and take me on lots of walks! I am a 1.5 year old English Bull Dog/American Bull Dog mix who currently weighs 80 lbs. I'm on a bit of a diet at the moment. Just a reminder, I am still a puppy (just an extra large one) who will need training and understanding. I do sometimes chew on things I'm not supposed to when I'm left alone and not safely in a crate, but that's all part of having a puppy. 

Applicants who are interested in adopting Moo Moo, will need to demonstrate patience and understanding. Once the initial screening takes place - via an adoption application, we will set up an initial meet and greet. From there, we will require you to take Moo Moo to multiple weekend training sessions (in Apopka at Natural Instinct Dog Training) while he still resides at our Sanctuary, upon completion of training, we will decide (with you), if Moo Moo is the right fit for you. 

Whoever we deem fit to care for this sweet boy, will have his everlasting affection, he couldn't be a more wonderful being!

My adoption fee is $500 and that includes my shots, neuter, microchip and training at Natural Instinct Dog Training (prior to adoption)!

animal.description:
Breed: American Staff Terrier
Gender: male, neutered
Estimated DOB: 7/25/17
Vaccinations: up to date
Heartworm Status: negative
Notes:  can be very selective with dogs, especially of the same size as him - he is not good with cats at all -- Owner mentions has been positive with children.

*Located in Baton Rouge*

Odin is not a CAAWS dog but a courtesy listing.  Email his caretaker at kdupuy@cox.net to inquire about adopting or for more information.

Information from caretaker:
Odin is a big boy with a big personality. A 3 year old 70lb American Staffordshire Terrier, this big bold goober is loyal to a fault and guaranteed to make you laugh. Unfortunately, he is not the best match for his current situation and would love a place to finish growing into his best self. He's looking for a new owner with a less crowded lifestyle to take and lead him into the next part of his life and give all his love to. He has already had a lot of training with plenty of room to grow. Crate trained with decent recall depending on his environment, he walks well on a leash, knows all the basics, eager to please and ready to play at a moment's notice. He's happy to spend the day on the couch with his favorite humans, however this muscleman needs his daily exercise. Sometimes personal space is foreign to him and he is not aware of his size as he snuggles up to get close to his favorite people. He just wants you to touch him and if you find that special spot on his chest and neck he'll beg you not to stop. He can be weary of new people around the ones he loves, especially in tight quarters, but warms up quickly when introduced properly. He's just looking for another compassionate and understanding owner that can provide him space he needs to feel secure and enjoy life. As far as other pets go, he does best with female dogs and most male dogs slightly smaller than him, but has had plenty of big male dog friends over his life. He has a long history of going to camp and interacting with other dogs, the majority of which has been positive. He loves to play rough with the ladies and some of the guys too if they are more submissive. Kitties are a no go. He is not suited for dog parks, as he does not stand down to any funny business from unknown dogs trying to be dominant.  All interactions with kids have been positive

animal.description:
I am currently being fostered in Washington. I already made the big journey from Texas to Washington so I would really like to stay in the PNW area. So if you live in Oregon or Washington I would love you to be my furever people. 
Meet Lunchbox JuM LunchBox is a kid's name for a big dog!! Although, if I were say, Batman LunchBox or ScoobyDoo LunchBox I would be ok with that, but just LUNCHBOX??? not so sure However, that is my name and it denotes some of my personal characteristics, I am SQUARE like a lunchbox :) I am filled with lots of good things and you may have to wait a little while to get to the gooey center of the lunch- cause I am a little shy to start out... So I am about 1.5 yrs old, saved on the border of TX and Mexico- trying to decide if it was a good idea to make a run for the border or not... for ME it was REALLY good idea, because I was seen by a great rescuer and SAVED!!! So I am a beefy boy, chow mix, and about 45#, I look like a lunchbox ;) but don't let that scare you- I am a sweetheart. I want so much to be loved and have a wonderful home. Children definitely make me nervous so I am best in an adult only home, I am good with other dogs and would be best with another kind of lazy, easy going dog. I am ready for love, hopefully you are too ;) Local adoption fee $200.00

animal.description:
Aries needs an emotional support human, he has had nothing but heartbreak these days. For months he sat in a crowded Los Angeles shelter without any attention, not a single walk, no human interaction other than to feed and water him.

The neglect he endured only made him crave human attention more.

Aries loves loves loves laying on his dog bed and sitting in front of the heater. He doesn't mind doing this while you are at work or working around the house. When you are on the couch he is going to come up for cuddles and affection.

His leg was amputated in early November so he is not the kind of dog that can run marathons or go for long hikes, he would rather keep you company indoors and watch your favorite show together.

While Aries does well with other large breed dogs, small crittes, dogs and puppies with too much energy make him nervous and he would do best in a home without them.

animal.description: Meet our sweet dude Ramsey!! Poor Ramsey was one of three dogs that were surrendered to us when his owner passed away unexpectedly to Diabetes.  He was in this loving home since he was a puppy - he is only about 3 to 4 years old.  He is neutered and up to date on all his shots.  We think he is house broken because he will not mess up in his kennel; however, we cannot be positive as some dogs act differently in a home than in a shelter environment.  Ramsey has completely stolen all of our hearts at BARK due to his unfortunate placement at BARK!!! He is good with female dogs but he is an alpha male.  He would due best in a home as the only dog or with a sweet female.  His owner had no cats so it is unknown how he would do around cats.  Ramsey has been around older children over the age of 12 years old and has done fine.  He has never been around young children but due to his size, we think he would do better with older kids. If you are interested in adopting Mr. Ramsey, please email us at LongJ1003@aol.com and Katybug6067@gmail.  We would love to speak to you more about him.

animal.description:
Granny has a story we wish she could tell us. You can see it in her eyes and on her body that life hasn't been kind to her.

Granny is looking for a family who can provide her a calm home where she can be loved. She was found with a young dog wondering the street. She didn't have a chip and no owner came for her. Unfortunately she was Heartworm positive and received treatment. 

Granny would do best with no other dogs or kitties. She would love to just sit by her foster and receive all the love imagineable. 

Do you have room in your house and heart to help Granny see life can be full of love? 

To set up a meet and greet or inquire about a dog, please first fill out an application at https://savinghoperescue.org/contact. It doesn't obligate you, but it is the first step. We don't get to all of the inquiries but respond to all applications. Thank you for choosing to rescue!

animal.breeds_label: American Staffordshire Terrier & Australian Cattle Dog / Blue Heeler Mix
animal.description:
WE WOULD LOVE TO FIND A FOSTER HOME FOR COOPER!

Date of birth:  8/21/2017

1/27/2021:  Cooper is an adorable American Staffordshire mix!  We think he’s mixed with Cattle Dog and/or Lab.  He is 3 years old and weighs 63 lbs but needs to gain a little more weight. 

• Cooper's had a rough life of neglect and a lack of companionship.  Given his history, he's an amazingly sweet natured dog.  He is timid and shy at first, but he warms up pretty quickly with patience and treats.  He loves to snuggle and give kisses, and he is sure that he’s a lap dog!  He’s a sensitive guy and wants to be with you once he knows you.

• Cooper needs a special home to help him overcome his lack of socialization. We're looking for someone who has experience as a dog parent,  is dog savvy and patient, and comfortable working with a dog who's been undersocialized.     

• Cooper will need a home without kids, cats or other dogs. He does get along with other dogs, but he's recently had a couple of altercations with his doggie friends here. At this point, we feel that having another dog in the home would be an additional challenge for him behaviorally, and he'd benefit from being an only pet. In the future, another dog companion may be a possibility.  

• He needs a house and yard with a secure wooden privacy fence. 

• Cooper's done well here with our male staff members, as well as our female staff.  We think he'll do fine with men as long as they are gentle with him.

 • We'd love to hear from you if you may be interested in fostering Cooper!  The shelter environment is very stressful for him and, although we're doing all we can for him, we would love to find him a foster home. 

• Cooper's very bright. He has a medium to medium-high energy and needs someone who is active and will take him for walks or jogs.  He pulls some on a leash, but he's not difficult to walk.  In the future, once he's bonded to his new person and less fearful, we could imagine him doing well in agility.

• Unfortunately, Cooper tested positive for heartworms.  Instead of the routine heartworm treatment, we are doing a treatment plan that is easier on a dog who is stressed.  He's been getting 2 doses of Advantage Multi twice a month, thru March 15. Then he'll go down to once a month, and be retested for heartworms in September.   We can fill you in more about his treatment plan if you are interested in fostering or adopting Cooper.  We're covering the costs associated.

• Cooper has been neutered, vaccinated and microchipped.  He’s a very sweet and loving guy and he’ll be a wonderful companion for the person who gives him a chance.

MORE ON ADOPTING OUR DOGS... 

> COVID-19 UPDATE:  PLEASE SUBMIT AN ONLINE ADOPTION APPLICATION AND A MEMBER OF OUR ADOPTIONS TEAM WILL REACH OUT TO YOU.  Please visit our web site at HSGKC.ORG for an adoption application, our current COVID-19 adoption protocol, and other adoption info. 

> If you decide you'd like to adopt one of the pets you meet, we reserve the pet for you but we generally don't send the pet home with you that day. We’ll instead schedule a pick up date and time that’s convenient for you.   

> Our goal is to send you home with a healthy pet and any information and support you may need to help your new pet adjust to his or her new home.  All of our dogs & puppies have been spayed or neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, treated for fleas & ticks, tested for heartworms (7 mo. and over), and are on monthly heartworm preventative. Puppies who are too young to receive all the necessary puppy boosters and/or first rabies shot may be brought back to us for those vaccines at no extra charge. You will also receive a leash, collar, coupons for pet supplies and services, toys, and educational materials. And we'll give your dog a bath before he or she goes home! 

> Please note that we prefer and may require a fenced yard for many of our dogs.  Exceptions are made on an individual basis depending on the dog's needs, the person's dog experience, the dog's and person's activity levels, home environment and other factors. 

Thank you for searching for a shelter pet!

11/7/2020:  River is a big handsome Lab/Shepherd mix! He’s 5 years old and weighs 76 lbs, with very long legs.  River is super friendly and loves people. 

• He’s very playful and loves to play with stuffed toys and gallop around the yard with them in his mouth!

• River does well playing with younger, playful female dogs. We've found that he doesn't do as well with male dogs. If you have an energetic female dog who's looking for a playmate, you could bring your dog to meet River to see if they could be buddies.

He’ll also need lots of exercise and mental stimulation to keep him busy and out of trouble! 

• River takes treats very gently and he’s pretty good about not jumping up on people. We think he’d be okay with kids who’ve been around a large dog and are very comfortable with that.

• He’s strong and will need someone who can handle walking a big strong dog. Training would benefit him.

• River keeps his kennel clean.  He has been neutered, vaccinated, microchipped and tested for heartworms.

animal.description:
He is currently in his foster home with Phantom K9 Training (IG: @phantomk9_) in Mesa, Arizona learning basic obedience. 

He likely came from a neglectful home, his nails were extremely long and causing him pain, the end of his tail was mutilated, and he was overall just in rough shape when we picked up. 

That being said, after a bath and some major TLC, Voyage is looking sharper than ever! 

He was very nervous upon arrival, and had clearly never been on a leash before or with a collar on. 

Despite his pain, nerves, and obvious mistreatment, Voyage has been EXTREMELY loving and friendly.  He is definitely going to turn out to be a velcro dog, loving his people! 

He is already crate and potty trained. 

He is very submissive and loving, and does great with other dogs as long as they are not overly pushy.

We are a rescue run by dog trainers! If you are not interested in or financially able to continue with the training and care we are providing for him please do not inquire. We strive to find the best home for our dogs that will give them the time, mental stimulation, physical exercise, and effort that they deserve.

Follow his progress/updates on IG through @shadesofbludogtraining @woofgangrehab and @phantomk9_

animal.description:
Tara is the sweetest, 12 month old, almost 45 lbs, bouncy, playful, goofy, smart, eager to please puppy. It can take her a bit to warm up to some new folks, yet others, she likes immediately. She has had such a crazy life so far, yet she is lovely and affectionate. She was dumped by her first family, as they had no time for her and did not train her, so another family got her off craigslist, where the 14 year old, sadistic daughter, beat this dog to try to make her into a guard/attack dog. (She also cut the tails off 2 kittens, thinking they were cuter with no tails!) A local shelter ended up with her (and the kittens), where she was crazy, being in a kennel all day long, so she did not show well, when folks came to meet her. Tara was originally posted as a coonhound mix, for the shelter saw her coloring and assumed that is what she is, but she is not a coonhound. She is a herder dog, for sure. She is in with 7 dogs and does fine, but one on one, folks need to be alpha, or she can be bossy and bratty at times, with another dog, but she does enjoy playing with another dog. She needs an experienced home that can get her more training and teach her stuff, for she is so smart and could probably be great at agility or some other cool type of training. She is not hyper, just smart and active and ready to learn. She is okay with some cats as well, but could chase. Great in the car, and crate trained and housebroken. A fenced yard is a must, and no young kids, for she might be too rough. A must meet, for she is so adorable in person, with all of her speckles and cute half mask. Please, open your hearts and home to this sweet pup - you will be so glad you did.  CRPUPS@PTD.NET to contact us for any reason. (If you do not hear back from us within about 6 hours, send us your phone number, for there might be something wrong with your email! WE DO NOT TEXT) 
Lovable Mutts Adoption Center is a private, in home, all breed rescue/adoption facility, specializing in all ages and sizes of dogs.  We exist only on the kindness of your donations and adoptions!  We pride ourselves on being an HOLISTIC center and feed only holistic grain free foods and give daily, various, vitamins and supplements to all of our dogs. 

Our dogs are well socialized, very friendly, well mannered, affectionate, and in wonderful health. While some might be timid or shy, we work with our adopters in any way we can, to help them to work with their new family member. We give training tips and behavioral tips and even board for a very reasonable fee. Our dogs are extremely well cared for - most even know how to use a dog door by the time they leave us, know basic commands, and are crate trained!  We stand by our pups/dogs, and give 10 days for a refund and almost always take our dogs back at any age of their lives (can sometimes depend on the dog)! 

Lovable Mutts Adoption Center has an application screening process.  All applicants are asked to provide vet references, personal references, and a home visit.  We pride ourselves in matching up the right dog with the right home.  Sometimes this happens quickly and sometimes it might take awhile.  We hope you understand and are willing to wait for the perfect pup for your situation. We reserve the right to turn applicants down and to change our mind about a suitable match, for we are only concerned about what is best for our dogs.  Also note that we arrange our visiting hours around your schedule, as this is a private, in home facility.  We respond to all inquiries promptly, so if you have any trouble sending us an email, or have not heard back from us within 24 hours, please, CONTACT US AGAIN and check your spam!  (We all know how emails can be at times!)

Our dogs are spayed or neutered (if old enough), up to date on vaccines, wormed, heartworm tested, and free of fleas and ticks.  We temperament test our  dogs and they are all suitable for many family situations. Our dogs are well mannered,  and are in our family/home situation at this time (not kept in kennels or crates), and are worked with daily.  All of our dogs do well with other dogs and many do well with cats, and we can cat test. Adoption donations vary with age, breed, vetting, and training of the dog, and range from $250 to $500. This donation helps to pay for shots, de-wormings, spays, neuters, flea protection, heartworm/Lyme testing, treatments, and other vetting/issues that might be needed, for dogs in our care.  (We do not tend to place puppies or small dogs with kids under 6 and reserve the right to match who WE feel would be the best homes for our dogs.)  
Please, come adopt one of our Lovable Mutts - you will be so glad you did!

(IF YOU DO NOT GET A REPLY EMAIL WITHIN 24 HOURS, CHECK YOUR SPAM BOX - WE REPLY EVERY FEW HOURS TO EMAILS)

She is not hyper, just smart and active and ready to learn. She is okay with some cats as well, but could chase. Great in the car, and crate trained and housebroken. A fenced yard is a must, and no young kids, for she might be too rough. A must meet, for she is so adorable in person, with all of her speckles and cute half mask. Please, open your hearts and home to this sweet pup - you will be so glad you did.  CRPUPS@PTD.NET to contact us for any reason. (Fostered in PA - We do not text) (If you do not hear back from us within about 6 hours, send us your phone number, for there is clearly something wrong with your email!) Dog's Best Friend Adoption Center utilizes an adoption application and screening process. We require personal and vet references and a home check made prior to adopting one of our dogs. All of our dogs are companion animals that must be kept inside the house with the rest of the family members. All of our dogs are temperament tested, well mannered, and know some basic commands ~ they are worked with daily, as someone is always here with them. All of our dogs do well with other dogs and many do well with cats. Adoption donations range from $250 to $450, depending on breed, age, size, vetting, and training of the dog (some pure bred and tiny dog fees are higher). This donation helps to pay for shots, de-wormings, spays, neuters, flea protection, heartworm/Lyme testing, treatments, and other vetting/issues that might be needed, for dogs in our care. Dog's Best Friend dogs truly make wonderful family pets. Please  email us for an application. (If you email us and do not hear back from us within 24 hours, please try again, as we most likely did not receive your email!) (Also note that many of our dogs are fostered just across the border into PA)

animal.description:
Hi there!  My name's Dudley, what's yours?!  I'm a happy go lucky kinda boy, and I'm looking for a nice new family who will love me forever and ever!!

I was brought to the shelter after someone found me as a stray.  I'm not sure where my family went, but I sure do miss them!  The vet thinks I'm only about a year old, so I have a lot of life ahead of me!!  I just need someone special to share it with!

A few things you should know about me are that I'm deaf and have some neurological concerns as well.  I don't let that hold me back though!  I still love going for walks and exploring the neighborhood, I also love to play!  I would do best in a home with someone who has experience with large special needs dogs, and who is ready to help teach me all the things a good doggie should know!!

The people here at the shelter have been working with me on some sign language to teach me how to sit, and I've been doing pretty well!  But I will need more training in a new home.

If you have room in your heart and house for a big guy like me, please stop by the shelter and spend some time getting to know me!

animal.description:
Freddy is around 4 years old, weighs a bit less than 50 lbs and was rescued from Puerto Rico, so he is a medium sized Sato, known for being extraordinarily loyal and loving dogs. He might not be the best pup to adopt if you have a cat, though.

His rescuer and foster says: As I went by Tropical Beach I saw a man in a wheelchair in the middle of the road. He was trying to help a dog that was hit by a car. The situation was crazy, no time for anything. I said if you can get him in the car, I'll get him to a vet.  The man and a woman who came rushing up, got him in the car (all this in less than 5 mins). I raced off to the vet clinic.  It was Sunday, but they opened the clinic, checked him out, and got him on pain meds (his pain was horrible). Next day X-rays showed a fractured spinal column and a fractured lower leg/paw.
Slowly he healed. Slowly began walking. The entire clinic fell in love with him. The vet keeps saying he is THE BEST DOG EVER "un caballero."
He will always walk funny, sort of bowlegged.  His front paw sort of doubles up on him sometimes but he corrects it instantly. He loves people! Right now he is just like "Too much down time, I want to play, sniff, run, sniff, enjoy, sniff. "
All through enormous pain, he never ever tried to bite or growl or anything. He is good with other dogs.  His big thing is to sniff them.
HE HAS THE ABSOLUTE BEST DOGGY SMILE!!

animal.description:
If interested in learning more or adopting, the next step is to complete our online application! 
https://pethavenmn.org/adopt/adoptable-dogs/dog-adoption-application/

Meet Luke! A 6yo Hound mix who is excited to find his forever home. 

Luke is 60-pounds of energy, love, and curiosity! His curiosity levels to that of a cat, who we have found would not be the best home companion for him. Luke’s enthusiasm to chase the cats is a little too much and so no cats for him. 

Luke is a wonderful balance of high energy playtimes and low-key cuddle sessions. He has the most amazing time on walks, sniffing everything there is to be sniffed and being on the lookout for squirrels.

When Luke is nervous, he does go to the nearest safe zone like under a table. He does best when you let him be and become comfortable again. Also, when he feels he is being confronted with commotion or too quickly, he does bark to let you know “hey, I need my space for a little bit” and then will go to his safe zone for a little bit to relax. This is also why we are recommending there be no kids in his forever home. 

Luke has met other dogs and is initially apprehensive, not sure what they are about, and sometimes he vocalizes this. With more introductions though, he does warm up. He might do well having another dog in the house who is patient and will show him the ropes and will need a slow introduction to start. 

 Luke is looking for an active home that will provide him with the ample daily exercise that he needs and loves. Also, a home with loving and patient humans who are willing to work with him on some of his manners and quirks. Finally, a home with a fenced yard would be amazing and give him the most happiness!




His adoption fee includes spay/neuter, heartworm/Lyme test, all age-appropriate vaccinations (distemper, rabies, & Bordetella), HW and flea/tick preventative, and microchip implant and registration. 

There is no guarantee of age and breed as a rescue animal's history is unknown. All ages and breeds are best guess.

Adoption fees INCLUDE a mandatory sales tax of 7.525%.

Due to post-adoption services provided, it is Pet Haven's policy to only place dogs into homes within a 75-mile radius of the Minneapolis, MN city center.

~~~~~
Toby for now- is just that - He needs a better name.... There is another thing that he needs too... A REAL Family!  How do you  love and live with a dog for two and a half to three years and leave him behind??? 
We don't get it , either!  He loves to hunker down under the covers and loves to do zooms around the house from time to time. He is a lover not a fighter- but this being said, we have NO IDEA what he feels about cats- 
He'd likely chase one- 
He appears to have another breed in him as well; not a pure - bred dog, but he is SO cheerful and sweet , you wouldn't care awnyway!  


~~~~~


Due to Covid-19 concerns, we are not planning any public adoption events. If you are pre approved , we will call to set up an appointment to come and meet the dog and potentially take them home. It is by appointment only- 
Dogs will be brought into the outdoor kennel for you to meet and make your decision. MASKS WILL BE MANDATORY to maintain EVERYONE'S safety  NO EXCEPTIONS PLEASE !! 
The puppies and dogs listed will arrive on Saturday, October 24th, 2020 .

http://littlerhodyrescue.com/adoption-application/ 

*Filling an application does not guarantee you as the adopter. All applicant's references will be called. PLEASE call your veterinarian and references consent to speaking with us ! 
We cannot process your application otherwise. Failure will put your application in 'Limbo"  
We process applications as they arrive. The first approved applicant will be called and the pup taken off of Petfinder. We do not have the man/ woman power to all all other applicants to advise them. 
IF there s another dog that you are interested in as well, please list at the top of the application and we will enter your application for that pup if the first choice has been adopted. 

THANK YOU !!! You are giving a first rate dog a second chance....By adopting! 

***** SADLY , we need to put this in print: THIS IS A RESCUE DOG. We do NOT know their birthday / age.  (unless other wise noted)  
More often than not, OUR TEAM  has saved them from euthanasia in Southern shelters. 
We do not know any more than our Veterinarians offer to us. 
 We often have them in kennels, and utilize crate training.  House training status is often NOT KNOWN. 
Prior Health, estimated weight  (as an adult), breed (Including the parents' breed , size or mix)   and some health concerns are  NOT KNOWN unless our veterinarians discover it and offer the information to us.   Again, these are strays and turn ins from all over the country. They do NOT come with labels; nor guarantees. 

Characteristics and disposition can and will evolve with time.
YOU the adopter are responsible to train and keep up to date on vaccines and preventatives.  
YOU the adopter are responsible for taking care of this new member of your family. 
 *************

****
Our adoption fees are $ 600. This fee includes the transportation of the pet from one of the organizations that we work with in TX, LA or TN. Before joining us in RI all dogs are: spayed/neutered, microchipped, up to date on age-appropriate vaccines, and on de-wormers, flea/tick and heartworm prevention. In addition, all adults (6 months +) are heartworm tested and MUST be negative for both heartworm and microfilaria before transport. 

In addition to the above, all dogs must have a Certificate of Veterinary Inspection and be deemed healthy per USDA law in order to travel. Once they have been certified they are then transported via USDA transport services only, which is required by law. 
 We  sometimes don't understand how bad the situation is for these pups and dogs in southern states.  Many people in the south don't spay or neuter their pets as we do here. Subsequently, there are thousands of beautiful , worthy pups and dogs, kittens and cats  that are dumped, shot, abandoned, brought into shelters, neglected, abused and abandoned.  We step in , tend to their veterinary needs. As you can see above, we never fail to properly spay and neuter. Everything is done with the  caring , capable hands of our veterinarians to get them healthy and ready to place them for adoption. That's when we put the demand for family- friendly pets with the supply ..... 

Give a first rate dog a second chance!!!! ADOPT! 


Keep in mind that we also offer a two week return policy for the return of a healthy dog that includes a full refund. We want to make sure that the adoption is a perfect fit for both you and the dog.

If you would like more information about adopting please select "More About Little Rhody Rescue" where you will also find our online application if you'd like to proceed with the adoption process. Thank you!

animal.description:
L Bonnie is a mature lady that ended up in rescue. She is now 10 years old and has unfortunately lost her family. She does great on a leash (pulls some when she spots a squirrel), loves to go for rides, loves everyone she meets and is a perfectly house mannered girl. Bonnie has gone to work with me at times and we all forget she is there - she just snoozes and hangs out. She has done okay with some dogs in rescue but it doesn't last long so I will be firm she needs to be an only dog - period. Because she is a older I would suggest no small children - she is past babysitting age. If small kids visit your home simply put her up and protect both her and the children from any incident. Sometimes we need to protect the dogs as much as they protect us. Bonnie gives the sweetest little nose kisses and absolutely loves her grown humans. She has met a horse, steer and goats with no interest. I do not know about cats. She also has an ugly scar on her front paw. She had a benign growth removed and was absolutely NOT having the cone. Bonnie really needs a home of her own to finish out her retirement years. She really is the sweetest girl and just tugging at my heartstrings to still be in the kennel. Please apply at www.krrtx.org/forms. 
Please note all dogs are located in San Antonio, TX. We advertise out of state due to the critical pet overpopulation problem here in the south. We use Our Texas Rescue Connection to transport the dogs to your area. They are all up to date and come with a health certificate. The fee is $170 adoption and $180 transportation = $350. Thank you for considering adopting a southern dog.

animal.description:
Meet Dusty. He's ton of fun in a small package. He's really friendly with people. Dusty enjoys chasing his herding ball around or playing fetch. He is a super high-energy dog and needs an active owner to help him burn off energy and get the exercise a young dog needs. If you're a runner, cyclist, hiker, or if you'd like a dog to have a job like agility, Dusty could be a great fit. He does well in his crate at night. Dusty plays well with other dogs, but he does like to pester them to initiate play. He would do best in a home without cats.

Dusty is a small, 1 year old blue male with a docked tail. He's neutered, vaccinated, and microchipped. He tested negative for heartworms and is taking heartworm prevention. He weighs 35 lbs.

Thanks for considering a dog from Texas Cattle Dog Rescue! We place heelers all over the state of Texas.

If you're interested in one of our dogs, please first complete our adoption application. You can download it at www.texascattledogrescue.com/adopt.html. Our standard adoption fee is $250 +tax for adult dogs, $300 +tax for puppies. Our dogs will be spayed or neutered, vaccinated and heartworm tested before going to a new home. We conduct a home visit to help match up the right dog with the right owner. For more information, visit our website www.texascattledogrescue.com.  Email adopt@texascattledogrescue.com if you have questions.

animal.description:
Meet Roscoe.  Roscoe is a big gorgeous stud!  This boy is handsome, affectionate, will greet you with hugs and kisses and is very people friendly.
 
Roscoe has made such huge improvements since arriving at his foster home.  When they first got him, he was skin and bones and barely knew how to walk due to living in a crate most of his life.  Roscoe had major skin issues and infections all over his body.  He was also afraid of being left alone and would cry.  Today, he's gained 20lbs and struts around like he owns the place =) He is goofy and expressive and always wants to be with the family, lounging on the couch and eating snacks.

He currently lives with two small dogs and another Pitbull, but is getting more selective with time, so would be best for him to be the only dog in the home.  He still has some separation anxiety though and would love someone who is patient and can continue to work on his crate training. 

His favorite game is fetch and he can't say no to a tennis ball!  Unlike the other dogs, he's not into soft squeaky toys.  However, his rubber bone is good too! 
He's a wonderful dog that needs the love and security of the perfect family.  Hoping that is yours! 


Please help us get sweet Roscoe into a safe, loving forever home!  If you're unable to help by adopting, sharing this post or donating is always appreciated.  Don't forget, Passion for Pitties is a 501(c)(3), so all donations are tax-deductible!…every little bit helps!
 
If you would like to adopt loving Roscoe, please fill out an application at www.passionforpitties.com under the “Adorable Adoptables” heading.

animal.description:
Breed: Smooth Collie/Anatolian Shepherd mix
Sex: Neutered Male
DOB: ~05/20/2016
Weight: 48 lbs
Energy Level: Low-Medium
Personality Type: Wallflower, Introverted, Loyal, Best Buddy
History: Transferred from another shelter
Good With: Dogs, Cats
Fence Requirements: Fenced yard, no invisible fences. Privacy fence preferred but not required.
Ideal Home: Single-person home or low-key couple. Calm, low-traffic homes where he can develop a routine are best. No apartments.
Special Info: Webster bonds very closely with his human. While he is not aggressive towards new people, he is very shy and keeps his circle small. He gets excited to see his person and wants to be near them at all times. Webster's adoption fee includes one free session with our force-free trainer.

The information we are providing for this animal was developed based on observations and assessments in a shelter or foster environment. We do our best to provide information that will help determine if the dog might be a good fit for you. Please note that behaviors may change in a home environment. We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.
