animal.description:
Quail is the sweetest, most playful pup you will ever meet! She’s about 2 years old and 45lbs of pure puppy happiness. 
She loves meeting new people and dogs. Quail enjoys snuggling next to you (or on top of you) but when she’s awake, she’s ready to play!

She’s very smart and a fast learner, is house trained and crate trained, but prefers room to play or to snuggle next to you. 
She’s a high energy girl who would love a human to spend quality, active time with her. She’d do best in a home with a yard and would love another pup who enjoys playtime as much as she does. She plays hard and loves harder! 

She’s exceptional on a leash but can get very excited if she sees a new doggo friend. She’s very food motivated, so she’ll learn quickly with a little attention and training. 

Quail is spayed, up to date on vaccinations and preventatives, and has almost completed her heartworm treatment. 
If you’re looking for a happy & cuddly new playmate, Quail might be your girl!

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2020 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

animal.description: How-do-you-do, my name is Benelli. In my spare time I was doing some research on my name and found it means "Warrior Maid" - I think that sounds quite valiant and noble. It also means I share a namesake with Joan of Arc and a beautiful race horse. I was returned to WCHS after 3 years by no fault of my own, my owner has a medical issue and was no longer able to give me the exercise I need. I have not had a lot of opportunity to learn proper manners but I know with daily exercise, a routine and training I will be an outstanding breed ambassador. I would be good with other dogs that are tolerant, and would likely do best with males, because I can get pushy and play rough - I am quite the spitfire. Any dog family I would need to meet to make sure we are good friends. Cats are an absolute no-no for me. I met a cat here and was quite rude with her. Although she tried to correct me, I ignored her wishes and was relentless; I simply have no respect for cats whatsoever. Children 12 years or older would be fabulous in my new home. I need the kids to be old enough to help me remember to keep four on the floor. Since I am about 55 pounds of muscle, if I jump up on a small person I know I could accidentally knock them over. I do OK with all sorts of handling as long as you don't mind me getting excited and jumping all over - just another opportunity for you to teach me some manners. I have stupendous manners with my food bowl and other valuable resources. I look forward to showing you how gently I accept treats if you ask me to sit. I also know how to catch and give kisses. I am quite the talented kiss-giver. I would love a long walk every day and other opportunities to burn some energy. I am very intelligent and think it would be fun to participate in mental activities where I can work my brilliant brain. I am playful and affectionate and promise to be a loyal and devoted companion. Come by to meet me in person and I am confident you will fall in love.
animal.name: Benelli

The Petfinder.com system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our dogs. animal.description:
Apartments, townhomes, condos, or basement suites will not be considered.  

Loki would prefer to be an only dog.  Definitely no male dogs in the home, no small dogs and no cats. 

Loki is looking for a home setting with a fenced area or fenced acreage. 

We WILL NOT respond to applications that do not have the experience to work on Loki's training needs 

If you are interested in adopting Loki, please read his full profile below.

An adoption application is required.  You can copy and paste the following link into your web browser

http://lowermainlandhumanesociety.org/adoption-application/

*********************

Loki is a 2 year old Great Pyrenees.  He was purchased to be a house pet, but the owners realized that their busy lifestyle taking care of 4 children and having to go to work, didn't leave them enough time to dedicate to training Loki or providing him enough physical and mental stimulation. 

When he was younger and smaller he was taken to the dog park often and was good with the dog he met there.  We tested him with several different large dogs here at the shelter and in home settings and this is what we know:

He has met 2 resident large female dogs and has hung out with them regularly on the property.  When he gets over excited and tries to rough play with them, he gets told off, and he backs off and finds something else to do. 

He has been in a home environment temporarily with neutered male dogs, however after a few days, he became over bearing towards the male dogs and tries to challenge them.  A home without male dogs is important..

He has played well with both female and neutered male dogs in open neutral settings such as a large fenced area. As long as the other dogs were not aggressive towards Loki. 

We haven't tested him with smaller dogs but we would say that he should not live with any due to his size and goofy puppy antics.

Unfortunately, Loki grew leary of the children in his previous home, therefore he should not go to a home with children of any age. 

Loki should not live with cats. 

We will not consider apartments, condos, townhomes, basement suites.   He is looking for a home environment with a fully fenced yard or fenced acreage (minimum 5.feet), where his people won't allow Loki to bark excessively.   He would greatly benefit from a home that understands that he is still young and needs consistent boundaries, routine, and rules..   his new owner MUST continue with his ongoing training needs. 

He has never been around farm animals, thus should not be with any.

He loves to hang out inside with his people, loves to get belly rubs and affection. He is very calm inside the house and loves to lounge around (as long as there aren't other animals to get him excited).  He should not be allowed on the furniture though :)

He's a good boy, and needs a human willing to put in the time and energy to provide leadership and training.  He still requires quite a bit of training, he pulls hard on leash and his recall is still a work in progress. 

He is neutered, microchipped, vaccinated, flea treated
 
His adoption fee is $395

An adoption application and home visit is required. 

You can find our application on our website 

http://lowermainlandhumanesociety.org/adoption-application/

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Loki should not live with male dogs, cats or farm animals.

animal.description: Everybody goes crazy for a well dressed man. That's Tux! Tux is a sweet boy who loves to cuddle and wants to be a lap dog. He is a smart, happy, content, playful adult who just wants to be wherever his people are! He's currently staying in an APA! foster home and is showing that he'll make a quick transition to his new home. Tux is very smart; he has wonderful manners and has been very well behaved in the house. He's housebroken and has had no accidents. He's trustworthy and hasn't gotten into any trouble, even when he's home alone. You'll find Tux to be a fantastic walking companion. He gets excited to go for his morning neighborhood walk and has great leash skills. He walks a few miles each day so he'll help you get in some extra exercise. Once back at home he enjoys a nice nap in the sun in the backyard. He's able to keep himself entertained by playing with his toys. Tux likes to toss and chase racquetballs, it's especially fun if you throw them for him! He also has his favorite rope chew toys and the stuffed fabric toys with the squeakers. He likes to have a basket where he can keep his toys organized so that he has easy access to whatever he feels like playing with next! Ultimately, Tux is a people-lover who is definitely happiest when he has his human(s) with him. He loves the people in his home, and has never met a stranger! Tux enjoys going for car rides, watching the world go by. As long as his people are close by, he'll be happy and content. And his people-pleasing attitude helps him learn rules and new commands quickly. Tux's personality will provide an even keel to your household. He would prefer to be the only pet in the household, though he'd like to be surrounded by as many people as possible. He is a sweet, loveable, happy boy who just wants everyone to love him back! A yard where he can get some extra exercise and sunbathing would be ideal. And don't forget, when you adopt from APA! you'll also be helping the next dog who can join us! Come meet Tux today!

animal.description:
Please do not apply if you do not have at least one other small/young dog in the home! 

To start the process to meet SUNNY, please fill out an adoption application. Meet and greets will be held in Tarzana, CA

https://pawsitivetailstoremember.forms-db.com/view.php?id=17980

SUNNY is 2 years old, she weighs 7.6  lbs, and is a tan and white female Chihuahua with a sweet but very shy face and personality. A little bit of history on Sunny’s past life; she was surrendered in June by her owner for a supposed bite incident to a finger who claims that she was given to him as a gift and he was losing his home and could no longer keep her. Her shelter video was heartbreaking and you could see her visibly shaking in her kennel; they made her RESCUE ONLY and the rescue community rallied around to network her and we ultimately took a chance and pulled her. Sunny was with our foster who specializes in behavioral dogs and she brought her to the next stage where we moved her to her current foster for more socialization. We do feel that she will only continue to thrive and to progress in her forever home. If we keep her too long with this foster it will completely set her back when we adopt her out.           

Sunny has definitely suffered trauma in her young life and she will require a special family to give her time to heal and to learn to trust people again. We do not recommend any young children in the home and she must have a quiet environment. We will NOT  consider any home that does not have a second small dog preferably a bit older but young enough to be able to interact and play with Sunny. 
 
Sunny Facts:

•	House trained using a doggie door (there will be a transition period in a new home)
•	Still perfecting her leash training, but I must say that she is doing great!
•	Sunny is extremely shy, lacks confidence and she will need a family willing to work on her issues in a calm and quiet manner. Sunny will need to trust you first, but she has come a very long way from the absolutely terrified and shaking dog that we rescued. 
•	Sunny loves other small dogs and is cat friendly
•	Sunny is microchipped, current on vaccines and is spayed 
•	This sweet and shy girl will continue to blossom with love and care and another dog in the home.

Like most dogs, Sunny would love nothing more than a warm lap and a family to call her own. She gets along well with other dogs and cats, therefore, there MUST be at least one other small dog in the home and she would do best in a quiet and calm environment with a retired couple, active single or a family with children 14 and older.

animal.description:
HAZEL is quite the character! You would never know she was found abandoned in Northern Arizona with a very limited chance of being adopted by a loving family there. When a plea was sent out for help, our rescue agreed to help find her that perfect home. This big goofball loves to play, chase the ball and roll over for endless tummy rubs. Check out that tongue, lots of kisses for everyone!!

Hazel will do best as the only dog in the household. Hazel is a good girl and loves to keep her kennel clean, so housetraining will be super easy when she gets into her own forever home. Hazel will do well when included as a 'family member' who will never be 'left outside, alone' again! She loves to please and will be so easy to teach basic, general commands. She is responding very quickly to leash training, too and will love a nice walk around the neighborhood as the weather starts to cool down. New sounds can startle her, so your patience will be appreciated when bringing her into your home. Remember how noisy those vacuums are or outdoor spraying sprinklers? She will look to you to reassure her that these are normal 'home' sounds.

Hazel has been vaccinated, microchipped and will be spayed this week. Her dream home should provide her with lots of human interaction and a great grassy yard to play in. Hazel is approximately 18 months old with a medium, stocky build and a great big, old head that just loves to be petted! She has a beautiful gray/brown coat with a super tuxedo chest. What a looker!

If you would like more info on Hazel, or want to meet her to see if she is a good match for your home, please complete our online application at www.helpadogsmile.org and a volunteer will be in contact with you. As we do home visits and stay in contact with each new owner during the adoption process, we limit our adoptions to the Phoenix metro area. Hazel's adoption fee of $250 helps with medical expenses of the rescue. Thank you for considering a loving rescue doggy!

Goober alert! Bodie is all puppy inside his brain. He is curious about absolutely everything, and follows that curiosity beyond reason. When he gets himself into a bind, he can really pour on the drama, putting on a world-class pout and keeping woe-is-me puppy-dog eyes at the ready to get sympathy. We confess - it works! Bodie is energetic and adventurous, tackling the playground equipment with happy abandon and impressive athleticism. He knows his manners but likes to see if maybe he doesn't have to use them (flash back to "puppy-dog eyes" and pouts). Treats, toys, and adorable head tilts round out his favorite things. Honestly, life is pretty much his favorite thing. [Unfortunately, tho, other animals are not his favorite. But he will bring you a wealth of entertainment as an only pet!]

animal.description:
Tigger and his sister Winnie are a bonded pair and need to find a home where they can stay together. They are both playful and house trained. They will probably be happiest in a home where they are the only pets. We did have Tigger's right eye looked at, and the vet said there was a puncture injury at some point, and it will heal over time. He can see some out of that eye.
*update: We hate to do this, but there has not been any interest in Winnie and Tigger except for a couple homes that have cats . We really would like to keep them together, but it looks like we may need to separate them. Having them sit in a kennel is not helping them, or the dogs we could have saved if we had their spots. We know it's asking a lot to adopt 2 dogs at once, and even with the added incentive of a partially sponsored adoption, there is no one applying for them. So, we are willing to split them up. They are both good dogs and house trained. Winnie takes treats very gently, Tigger not so much. Winnie sits right away when you ask, Tigger likes to stand on his back legs like, well, Tigger! Winnie loves toys. They did live with other dogs at their foster home down south, but up here we haven't had any luck with matching them up with play mates. 
Both don't like cats. Tigger is about 7 years old and 50#. Winnie is about 5 years old and 65#. 

We know they came from the same household in Alabama, and that their owner knew they were at the Chattahoochee Humane Society, and never went and got them. Tigger has some suspicious scars on him, so it's probably best they didn't come back for them. 
Their adoption fee has been partially sponsored if adopted together!
The adoption application can be found at www.northcountrypetadoption.org

animal.description:
Jack is approximately 1 1/2 years old. He is a border collie/blue heeler mix. Jack is very obedient and just wants to please. He is good off leash and on leash. He gets along well with other dogs and is a bit afraid of the cats. We have learned that Jack needs another dog for confidence. He will do best in a home with another dog that is confident that can show him the ropes. When he is in a home environment without another dog, he is anxious and nervous and will try to hide. Transitioning to a new home will take him some time to adjust but if you have patience, he is such loving dog.
Jack's ideal home would be a farm type environment. He has spent most of his life outside, so he is not very comfortable in a home and will need time to adjust to house living. He loves to be out with the animals and following his owner around. He would probably do best in a home with older dog savvy children as loud noises and quick movements can make him nervous. When he gets worried, his reaction is to run back to his kennel. He prefers to hide when he is nervous.
Jack has been neutered, is up to date on his vaccinations and is micro-chipped. Schedule a time to come meet this sweet dog today!

animal.description: Hello!  My name is Monami (pronounced “moan-ah-mee”, HWTH#20203A).  I am a Husky mix, born on 9-1-19 and I weigh 40 lbs. My name is the combination of two French words “mon” and “ami” which mean “my friend”.    I came to Halfway to Home shortly after I was adopted from the Lancaster shelter because my owner passed away.  I am looking for a special mature and compassionate person or couple to give me a forever home with a lot of love and understanding.   I have a neurological condition called cerebral hyperplasia.  It is caused by the underdevelopment of a part of my brain called the cerebellum, which is responsible for coordination, balance and depth perception.  I appear to have only mild symptoms, and only in rare cases does it get worse over time.  The most obvious symptoms I have is that I walk very “carefully” because I perceive myself being off-balance (very similar to a horse gait), and when you try to give me a treat or throw me ball, I don’t see it right away so it takes a little while for me to find it.  I can still run and play, but it is important that my new home keep me safe from self-harm that can be caused by small obstacles or uneven surfaces.  Stairs are very challenging for me so I would need someone with me to guide me up and down.  Loud noises startle me so I need a quiet home with no children or other pets.  Other than my physical challenges, I am like other Huskies.  I love to “talk” and will engage in conversations with my humans.  Regular brushing is needed because I shed more than most breeds.  A fenced yard would be preferable but I would probably be ok in a condo or apartment as long as it is on the ground floor and I get daily walks to keep me stimulated and fit.  So, what do you think?  Would you like to be “mon ami”?  I have a lot of love to give and with some patience I think you will see that I make a wonderful companion.   If you are interested in learning more about me or making an appointment to meet me, please call Sandy at tele#661-824-4495 (this is a landline).  I hope to meet you soon!

animal.description:
IF INTERESTED, PLEASE SUBMIT AN APPLICATION ON OUR WEBSITE:
https://www.wonderdogrescue.org/adoption-application

All animals are spayed/neutered as part of the adoption process if they are not already.

Daisy is a chihuahua who was very frightened at the shelter. She came to us crying out in (apparent) pain so often that we wondered how severe her health condition actually was. Well, per our veterinarian, Daisy is just scared of being handled by strangers. The moment this little doll settles into your home she will lavish you with love and attention. Daisy is the kind of little dog who really wants to be someone's dog. We can tell that although she gets along ok with other dogs, she really was an only dog- though she does play with the neighbor's dog at her foster home. She seeks and gives so much affection.

Daisy has been to the vet and we've done the typical blood workup on her. Our vet told us that while we thought she was a senior, she may actually be much closer to 5, given her health and the condition of her teeth.

So, if you want an adorable companion and are willing to put in a little time initially to acclimate her to your home, Daisy is your girl!  No youth under the age of 12 please.

animal.description:
Rocky is always excited to do something, anything, with you. He would love a home that is active as he has lots of energy. He is currently at our farm and learning about farm animals. He does well with other dogs with proper introductions. Rocky does well off leash on the farm and has good recall. In a more urban environment a leash would be best. He will need some work on leash as he likes to pull a bit.

Rocky came to us as a stray so we don't have much information about his background. He is good about just sleeping on his bed and not destroying it, so he has likely been an indoor dog. He likes to play with toys but is also content to just investigate his area. He is very friendly and happy to see people, but with his high energy he would be best in a home with older children.

He is now neutered, up to date on all shots and is microchipped. If you would like to meet Rocky, please email or call us to set up a meet and greet.

Petite and cute Betty is the perfect little package. Betty came into Cody's from a local shelter. She is around 4 years old and 40lbs. In her foster home she is learning how to play with dogs, learning crate training, and potty training. She will need a very solid crate as she does not love being crated.. She loves people and has never met a stranger. We haven't seen her around children but we think she would be great with kids - the more love the better for Betty. She is heart worm positive but we are treating her and she will be just fine. 

Overall Betty is a very calm dog. She prefers snuggling with her humans but loves to play with other dogs of all sizes. . Betty enjoys walks and would do fine in an apartment (must not have breed restrictions) or house. She does have separation anxiety so would love a home where home more than not. She hass burns on her back and we do't think she was loved in her previous home. She cowers and runs sometimes but we just love on her even more.

Betty can be a little shy in new situations and she would love an adopter who can continue to love her and build her confidence.

 

Applications are at https://bit.ly/codys_adoption_application.

She would do best in a home with carpeted floors but does well with grippy socks in her foster home. She is inquisitive, loving and smart as a whip. If you have a couch but no cuddle buddy, consider adopting Shatzi!

Shatzi is current on vaccines, spayed and microchipped.

animal.description:
Meet Belle!  She is a two year old mixed breed bundle of energy, likely part pit bull.  She is a rescue that we got Christmas, 2018.  Belle is spayed, up to date on all shots, heart worm negative, chipped and very healthy.  She weighs about 65 pounds and is very athletic and fast.  Belle loves to run, chase and catch tennis balls, and go for walks.  She’s very enthusiastic when meeting people and enjoys playing with our grandkids. Belle is selective in her dog friends and can become anxious around other dogs.  She has never been around cats.  Belle is house trained and enjoys her bath and shoulder massages.  She likes belly rubs and going to her crate for naps.  She learns quickly and knows basic commands.  Belle can jump high and needs a 6 foot fenced in yard.  She enjoys sitting on the patio with us and relaxing in the sun.  We are senior citizens, and Belle has become too strong for us to handle.  She would thrive with a younger, athletic family.  We love her dearly but realize she needs a more active environment than we can provide.  Please consider Belle as an addition to your family.

If interested in Bell please email rideaususan@gmail.com
